{"title_page": "Marshall Dlamini", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Marshall Dlamini\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = Secretary-General of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n| deputy              = [[Poppy Mailola]]\n| president           = [[Julius Malema]]\n| term_start          = 14 December 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Godrich Gardee]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| term_start1         = 21 April 2015\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = \n| successor1          = \n| birthname           = Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1977|08|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         =  [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] (former)\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Business<br/>Politician\n| known_for           = \n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Mineral Resources and Energy\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini''' (born 13 August 1977) is a South African businessman and politician. He is the current Secretary-General of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]], elected in December 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahlakoana |first1=Theto |title=EFF\u2019s new top 6: Mpofu\u2019s belly flop while Malema, Shivambu retain top positions |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/15/eff-s-new-top-6-mpofu-s-belly-flop-while-malema-shivambu-retain-top-positions |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=15 December 2019|location=Johannesburg}}</ref> He has been serving as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] since April 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nhlabathi |first1=Hlengiwe |title=Replaced EFF MPs vow to fight to the bitter end |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2015-04-25-replaced-eff-mps-vow-to-fight-to-the-bitter-end/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=25 April 2015}}</ref> Dlamini is a party member of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) and has been since its inception in 2013.\n\n==Political career==\nDlamini was previously involved in the [[African National Congress]] and its [[African National Congress Youth League|youth league]]. He was close to the league's former treasurer-general [[Sindiso Magaqa]].<ref name=\"TSA\">{{cite news |last1=Chothia |first1=Andrea |title=Marshall Dlamini rumoured to become new EFF secretary-general |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/marshall-dlamini-new-eff-secretary-general/ |accessdate=11 December 2019 |newspaper=The South African |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe became a member of the EFF in the early days of the party. He was in attendance at the party's launch at Uncle Tom's Hall in [[Soweto]] in July 2013. He was elected to serve on the Central Command Team, the party's highest decision-making structure.<ref name=\"TSA\" />\n\nHe became a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] in April 2015 following the expulsion of multiple EFF MPs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phalaetsile |first1=Olivia |title=EFF inaugurates new MPs |url=https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/eff-inaugurates-new-mps/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=jacarandafm.co.za |date=21 April 2015}}</ref> He was re-elected to a second term as MP in May 2019.\n\nAhead of the EFF's second leadership conference in December 2019, ''[[The Sunday Times (South Africa)|The Sunday Times]]'' reported that supporters of EFF president [[Julius Malema]] had begun to lobby for Dlamini to succeed incumbent [[Godrich Gardee]] as Secretary-General.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Makinana |first1=Andisiwe |title=Julius Malema 'prefers' slap-happy MP Marshall Dlamini for leadership job |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-06-julius-malema-prefers-slap-happy-mp-marshall-dlamini-for-leadership-job/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=6 October 2019 |quote=Supporters of EFF leader Julius Malema want controversial MP Marshall Dlamini to replace Godrich Gardee as the party's secretary-general.  This is according to several sources in the EFF who this week indicated that those close to Malema have begun lobbying for Dlamini to be elected as the new secretary-general at the party's national congress in December.}}</ref> At the conference, Dlamini was elected to the position unopposed. He is deputised by [[Poppy Mailola]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=Julius Malema re-elected EFF leader amid changes in the Top Six |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/eff-national-peoples-assembly-malema-top-six-15-december-2019/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Malema, Shivambu retain positions, but big changes in rest of EFF leadership |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2219332/malema-shivambu-retain-positions-but-big-changes-in-rest-of-eff-leadership/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn February 2019, following the State of the Nation Address, Dlamini physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team due to a conflict between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordaan |first1=Nomahlubi |title=WATCH l EFF MP slaps man in Sona scuffle |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2019-02-08-watch--eff-mp-slaps-man-in-sona-scuffle/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=DispatchLIVE |date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/mzingisi-marshall-dlamini/ Mr Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini \u2013 People's Assembly]\n*[https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/51 Mr Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini \u2013 Parliament of South Africa]\n\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dlamini, Marshall}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:South African pan-Africanists]]\n[[Category:Racism in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Anti-white racism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Marshall Dlamini\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = Secretary-General of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n| deputy              = [[Poppy Mailola]]\n| president           = [[Julius Malema]]\n| term_start          = 14 December 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Godrich Gardee]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| term_start1         = 21 April 2015\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = \n| successor1          = \n| birthname           = Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1977|08|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         =  [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] (former)\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Business<br/>Politician\n| known_for           = \n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Mineral Resources and Energy\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini''' (born 13 August 1977) is a South African businessman and politician. He is the current Secretary-General of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]], elected in December 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahlakoana |first1=Theto |title=EFF\u2019s new top 6: Mpofu\u2019s belly flop while Malema, Shivambu retain top positions |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/15/eff-s-new-top-6-mpofu-s-belly-flop-while-malema-shivambu-retain-top-positions |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=15 December 2019|location=Johannesburg}}</ref> He has been serving as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] since April 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nhlabathi |first1=Hlengiwe |title=Replaced EFF MPs vow to fight to the bitter end |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2015-04-25-replaced-eff-mps-vow-to-fight-to-the-bitter-end/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=25 April 2015}}</ref> Dlamini is a party member of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) and has been since its inception in 2013.\n==Political career==\nDlamini was previously involved in the [[African National Congress]] and its [[African National Congress Youth League|youth league]]. He was close to the league's former treasurer-general [[Sindiso Magaqa]].<ref name=\"TSA\">{{cite news |last1=Chothia |first1=Andrea |title=Marshall Dlamini rumoured to become new EFF secretary-general |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/marshall-dlamini-new-eff-secretary-general/ |accessdate=11 December 2019 |newspaper=The South African |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe became a member of the EFF in the early days of the party. He was in attendance at the party's launch at Uncle Tom\u2019s Hall in [[Soweto]] in July 2013. He was elected to serve on the Central Command Team, the party's highest decision-making structure.<ref name=\"TSA\" />\n\nHe became a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] in April 2015 following the expulsion of multiple EFF MPs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phalaetsile |first1=Olivia |title=EFF inaugurates new MPs |url=https://www.jacarandafm.com/news/news/eff-inaugurates-new-mps/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=jacarandafm.co.za |date=21 April 2015}}</ref> He was re-elected to a second term as MP in May 2019.\n\nAhead of the EFF's second leadership conference in December 2019, ''[[The Sunday Times (South Africa)|The Sunday Times]]'' reported that supporters of EFF president [[Julius Malema]] had begun to lobby for Dlamini to succeed incumbent [[Godrich Gardee]] as Secretary-General.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Makinana |first1=Andisiwe |title=Julius Malema 'prefers' slap-happy MP Marshall Dlamini for leadership job |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-10-06-julius-malema-prefers-slap-happy-mp-marshall-dlamini-for-leadership-job/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=6 October 2019 |quote=Supporters of EFF leader Julius Malema want controversial MP Marshall Dlamini to replace Godrich Gardee as the party's secretary-general.  This is according to several sources in the EFF who this week indicated that those close to Malema have begun lobbying for Dlamini to be elected as the new secretary-general at the party's national congress in December.}}</ref> At the conference, Dlamini was elected to the position unopposed. He is deputised by [[Poppy Mailola]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joubert |first1=Jan-Jan |title=Julius Malema re-elected EFF leader amid changes in the Top Six |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/eff-national-peoples-assembly-malema-top-six-15-december-2019/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The South African |date=15 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Malema, Shivambu retain positions, but big changes in rest of EFF leadership |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2219332/malema-shivambu-retain-positions-but-big-changes-in-rest-of-eff-leadership/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn February 2019, following the State of the Nation Address, Dlamini physically assaulted a member of the presidential security team due to a conflict between EFF MPs and the security.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jordaan |first1=Nomahlubi |title=WATCH l EFF MP slaps man in Sona scuffle |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2019-02-08-watch--eff-mp-slaps-man-in-sona-scuffle/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=DispatchLIVE |date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/mzingisi-marshall-dlamini/ Mr Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini \u2013 People's Assembly]\n*[https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/51 Mr Marshall Mzingisi Dlamini \u2013 Parliament of South Africa]\n\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dlamini, Marshall}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]