n Books|isbn=978-0-7391-1113-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Palmer|first1=Bill|last2=Palmer|first2=Karen|last3=Meyers|first3=Ric|title=The Encyclopedia of Martial Arts Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvOWrZ4WJHwC&pg=PA53|year= 1995|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-1-4616-7275-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Parish|first1=James Robert|last2=Marill|first2=Alvin H.|title=The Cinema of Edward G. Robinson|url=https://archive.org/details/cinemaofedwardgr0000pari|url-access=registration|year=1972|publisher=A. S. Barnes|isbn=978-0-498-07875-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Phillips|first=Gene D.|author-link=Gene D. Phillips|title=Beyond the Epic: The Life and Films of David Lean|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8131-2415-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bKtQTBGaB3wC&pg=PA358|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ray|first=Fred Olen|title=The New Poverty Row: Independent Filmmakers as Distributors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9GknfDYd4sC&pg=PA184|year= 1991|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-89950-628-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rees|first1=Dafydd|last2=Crampton|first2=Luke|title=Rock Stars Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/rockstarsencyclo00rees|url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=DK Pub.|isbn=978-0-7894-4613-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robe|first=Lucy Barry|title=Co-starring famous women and alcohol|url=https://archive.org/details/costarringfamous00robe|url-access=registration|year=1986|publisher=CompCare Publications|isbn=978-0-89638-100-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rollins|first=Peter C.|title=Hollywood As Historian: American Film in a Cultural Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x44fBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA161|year= 2015|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-4864-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Schilling|first1=Jerry|last2=Crisafulli|first2=Chuck|title=Me and a Guy Named Elvis: My Lifelong Friendship with Elvis Presley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jn323M63PAC&pg=PT99|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-101-21681-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Scial\u00f2|first=P.|title=La sceneggiata. Rappresentazioni di un genere popolare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nqY9qxaAUh4C&pg=PA167|year=2002|publisher=Guida Editori|isbn=978-88-7188-689-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Scott|first=James F.|title=Film, the medium and the maker|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7WVZAAAAMAAJ|year= 1975|publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston|isbn=978-0-03-079445-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shipman|first=David|title=The Great Movie Stars: The International Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P8IHAQAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Angus and Robertson|isbn=978-0-207-95858-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Simpson|first=Paul|title=Movie Lists: 397 Ways to Pick a DVD|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YnUfSocAlpYC&pg=PA92|year= 2011|publisher=Profile Books|isbn=978-1-84765-355-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stempel|first=Tom|title=Storytellers to the Nation: A History of American Television Writing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFTZrcyWnswC&pg=PA50|year=1996|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-0368-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Talbott|first=Strobe|title=The Great Experiment: The Story of Ancient Empires, Modern States, and the Quest for a Global Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WIUE8Y9-wYAC&pg=PA244|year= 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-7432-9409-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Terrace|first=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010, 2d ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YX_daEhlnbsC&pg=PA620|year= 2008|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8641-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=John Herd|last2=Randall|first2=Stephen J.|title=Canada and the United States: Ambivalent Allies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4KxDd4K1X-gC&pg=PA245|year= 2010|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-3725-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John|title=The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst |year=2005|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=0-446-69334-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wise|first1=James E.|last2=Rehill|first2=Anne Collier|title=Stars in the Corps: Movie Actors in the United States Marines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l3Z78rt_oHsC&pg=PA107|year=1999|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-55750-949-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wise|first1=James E.|last2=Rehill|first2=Anne Collier|title=Stars in Blue: Movie Actors in America's Sea Services|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h__ResgZNz4C&pg=PA241|year= 2007|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-59114-944-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wojcik|first=Pamela Robertson|title=Movie Acting, the Film Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5qDxCG7gx8C&pg=PA139|year=2004|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-31025-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Zimmerman|first=Steve|title=Food in the Movies|edition= 2d |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cZkcG-ftcaAC&pg=PA95|year= 2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5569-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Rod Steiger}}\n* {{IMDb name|1768}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* [http://moviemorlocks.com/2010/07/24/he-blowed-up-real-good/#more-25092.htm He Blowed Up Real Good (TCM Movie Morlocks on Rod Steiger in Hennessy)]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0094215 Rod Steiger] interview on BBC Radio 4 ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', July 14, 2002\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Rod Steiger\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestActor 1961-1980}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actor 1960-1979}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actor}}\n{{GoldenGlobeAwardBestActorMotionPictureDrama 1961-1980}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steiger, Rod}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Actor Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Actor BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Westhampton, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:West Side High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Sweney ye news", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActing style:fixed typo: coverage -> courage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_Steiger"}
{"title_page": "Joint Task Force Guantanamo", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Joint Task Force Guantanamo\n|image=JTFGTMO logo.png\n|image_size=100px\n|caption=\n|dates= November 2002 \u2013 present\n|country= {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America}}}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=Joint\n|type=\n|role=\n|size=\n|command_structure=[[United States Southern Command]]\n|current_commander= [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]]\n|garrison=[[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]]\n|nickname=\n|motto=Honor Bound to Defend Freedom<ref name=TheWireJtfGtmo>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/wire/WirePDF/issue47v8.pdf#15\n| title=Honor Bound to Defend Freedom| page=15| publisher=[[The Wire (JTF-GTMO)]]| author=Carlos Sanchez\n| date=January 17, 2008| accessdate=2008-02-10}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n|identification_symbol=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|notable_commanders=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n}}\n'''Joint Task Force Guantanamo''' ('''JTF-GTMO''') is a [[U.S. military]] [[joint task force]] based at  [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]], [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay, Cuba]] on the southeastern end of the base. JTF-GTMO falls under [[US Southern Command]]. Since January 2002 the command has operated the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s [[Camp X-Ray]] and its successors [[Camp Delta]], Camp V, and Camp Echo, where detained prisoners are held who have been captured in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|the war in Afghanistan]] and elsewhere since the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]. From the command's founding in 2002 to early 2017, the detainee population has been reduced from 779 to 41.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\">{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Carol|date=January 19, 2017|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article127473314.html|title=Obama to leave with 41 captives still at Guant\u00e1namo, blames politics|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref> As of May 2019, the unit is under the command of [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]].<ref name=Kuehas>{{cite web |url=https://www.southcom.mil/News/PressReleases/Article/1836670/news-release-jtf-gtmo-assumption-of-command/ |title=News Release: JTF-GTMO Assumption of Command |author=SOUTHCOM Public Affairs  |publisher=U.S. Southern Command |date=May 4, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{wikisource|Detention, Treatment, and Trial of Certain Non-Citizens in the War Against Terrorism}}\nIn 1992, the United States established [[Operation Sea Signal]] to prepare for a mass migration of refugees from Haiti and Cuba.<ref>JTF-GTMO, [http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg3.pdf Joint Task Force Guantanamo Timeline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308002848/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg3.pdf |date=2010-03-08 }}, accessed May 2010</ref> In 1994, Operation Sea Signal led to the creation of Joint Task Force 160. JTF 160 was responsible for housing and processing more than 40,000 migrants awaiting repatriation or parole to the United States. [[Camp X-Ray]] was established to segregate migrants who had committed crimes, such as theft, assault and battery, prostitution and black-market activities, from other migrants and from U.S. civilians and military personnel at Guantanamo. In 1996, Operation Sea Signal came to an end and the military abandoned Camp X-Ray.\n\nIn December 2001, after the [[September 11 terrorist attacks]] and the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|United States intervention in Afghanistan]], Joint Task Force 160 was reactivated. Camp X-Ray was prepared as a temporary location for the detention of people captured in Afghanistan who were believed to be part of the Taliban or al-Qaeda, neither of which the United States recognized as legal governments. In January 2002, the first [[detainees]] were transferred to Guantanamo Bay and housed in Camp X-Ray. The [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] (ICRC) had its first visit to the facility six days later. The ICRC has continued quarterly visits up to 2010.\n\n==Detention facilities==\nIn April 2002, construction of the new 410-bed [[Camp Delta]] (Camps 1, 2, 3) was completed. The detainees were moved from Camp X-Ray to Camp Delta that month. In November 2002, Joint Task Force 160 and 170 were merged to create Joint Task Force Guantanamo.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nBy 2007 original Camp Delta compound was supplemented by Camps 4, 5 and 6.\n\nCamp 4, opened in February 2003, featured communal style living areas, similar to a military barracks, and was used to house \"compliant\" detainees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2008/us0608/2.htm|title=Locked Up Alone: Detention Conditions and Mental Health at Guantanamo: II. The Range of Prison Facilities at Guantanamo|website=www.hrw.org}}</ref>\n\nCamp 5, opened in May 2004, had segregated housing units (i.e. solitary cells) for detainees who are uncompliant or who pose a threat to other detainees or Joint Task Force staff members.  Camp 5 was closed in 2016 when the total detainee population was reduced to 61.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article100496357.html|title=Guant\u00e1namo downsizes by closing one prison, cutting 400 troops|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCamp 6, opened in November 2006, is patterned after a medium security prison with \"pods\" housing 10 to 20 detainees with individual cells but sharing a common living area.  Camp 6 houses the \"general population\".\n\nAs of late 2016, almost all detainees were housed in Camp 6.\n\n==Status of detainees==\n\nThe status of these detainees is disputed. The [[United States]] government defines them as [[enemy combatant]]s, claiming their status was not that of a [[prisoner of war]] as recognized under the [[Geneva Conventions]] (due to not being affiliated with any government, being alleged members of [[Al Qaida]] or groups affiliated with them).\n\nIn ''[[Rasul v Bush]]'' (2004), the Supreme Court held that the detainees had the right to counsel and to challenge their detentions at an impartial tribunal, according to ''habeas corpus''. On June 29, 2006, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in  ''[[Hamdan v. Rumsfeld]]'' that they had the minimal protection of [[Wikisource:Third Geneva Convention#Article 3|Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions]] in that detainees must be housed and treated humanely, and that they had the right to an impartial tribunal to hear charges against them. It said the military tribunals as established by the Dept. of Defense did not have sufficient authority, and Congress needed to authorize any system outside the established US civil and military justice systems.\n<!--Other parties{{Who|date=January 2008}} insist that the captives be granted full [[prisoner of war]] rights and privileges listed in the Geneva Convention.-->In ''[[Boumediene v. Bush]]'' (2008), the Supreme Court held that the detainees' right to ''habeas corpus'' could not be taken away by the [[Military Commission Act of 2006]], which they ruled was unconstitutional. In addition, the Supreme Court held that detainees had the right to access federal courts to hear their ''[[habeas corpus]]'' challenges. Some of the cases are proceeding through the federal court system.\n\n==Intelligence task forces==\nIn February 2002, Joint Task Force 170 was created as the intelligence task force to work side by side with Joint Task Force 160.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}  At a later date, JTF 170 was re-designated as the Joint Intelligence Group and was assigned as a subordinate element of Joint Task Force Guantanamo.  The other subordinate elements of JTF GTMO are the Joint Detention Group and the Joint Medical Group.\n\n==Joint Detention Group==\nThe Joint Detention Group is one of the components of the Task Force. It is the organization assigned to guarding the captives, and maintaining camp security.<ref name=BrochureJDG>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg6.pdf\n |title       = Detainee operations\n |publisher   = Joint Task Force Guantanamo\n |year        = 2009\n |accessdate  = 2010-01-22\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100308002639/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg6.pdf\n |archivedate = 2010-03-08\n}}</ref>\nThe guards within the Joint Detention Group come from the [[United States Army]], [[United States Navy]], and other [[United States Armed Services]].\n\nIn 2009, guards outnumbered prisoners in Guantanamo by more than five to one.\n\nThe officers commanding the Joint Detention Group, also known as the warden, have included:\n*[[Colonel]] [[Adolph McQueen]], 2002<ref name=BostonGlobe2002>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2003/09/14/detainees_in_cuba_get_appetizing_incentives/| title=Detainees in Cuba get appetizing incentives| publisher=[[Boston Globe]]| date=2003-09-14| author=Dan Fesperman }}</ref>\n*Colonel [[Michael Bumgarner]], 2006\n*Colonel [[Bruce Vargo]], 2008\u20132010\n*Colonel [[Donnie Thomas (US Army)|Donnie Thomas]], 2010\u20132012\n*Colonel [[John Bogdan]], 2012\u20132014<ref name=Jtf-Gtmo2012-06-08>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xwebsite/print/stories/2012/06June/02JDG.html\n |title       = Warrior Six Signing Off\n |publisher   = [[JTF Guantanamo Public Affairs]]\n |author      = Lewis Hilburn\n |date        = 2012-06-02\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil%2Fxwebsite%2Fprint%2Fstories%2F2012%2F06June%2F02JDG.html&date=2013-03-24\n |archivedate = 2013-03-24\n}}</ref>\n*Colonel David Heath, 2014\u20132016<ref>[http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/News/Articles/Article/1063567/joint-detention-group-change-of-command/ Joint Detention Group Change of Command] JTF GTMO Public Affairs. July 1, 2016</ref>\n*Colonel Stephen Gabavics, 2016\u20132018\n*Colonel Steven Yamashita 2018\u2013Present\n\n==Living quarters==\nEnlisted personnel live in pre-fabicated quarters, similar to shipping containers.<ref name=AFPSEnlisted20050225>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25798\n| title=Guantanamo Troops Deployed in Unusual Surroundings\n| publisher=[[American Forces Press Service]]\n| author=[[:s:Kathleen Rhem|Kathleen T. Rhem]]\n| date=February 25, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-25\n| quote=Living conditions vary considerably within the JTF. Enlisted service members generally live in prefabricated individual buildings, which they call \"houses\" with a touch of cynicism. The shipping-container-like quarters each house four to six servicemembers. The troops typically divide the space as evenly as possible and then partition \"rooms\" by hanging blankets and shower curtains.\n}}</ref> Each prefab unit houses four to six personnel.  Each prefab unit ships with a toilet and sink, but no internal partitions. Occupants are allowed to erect curtains to make temporary partitions, for privacy. Occupants share communal showers, shared between prefab quarters.\n\nOfficers and senior non-commissioned officers typically share cottages left over from family residences that were constructed when the base had a larger permanent population.<ref name=AFPSOfficers20050225>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25798\n| title=Guantanamo Troops Deployed in Unusual Surroundings\n| publisher=[[American Forces Press Service]]\n| author=[[:s:Kathleen Rhem|Kathleen T. Rhem]]\n| date=February 25, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-25\n| quote=Senior enlisted members and officers generally live in converted Navy family housing left over from when the base housed a larger population of permanent-party personnel. For instance, one two-bedroom apartment might be assigned to four junior officers.\n}}</ref><ref name=JagMagWinter2007>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/news/jag_mag/archive/2007_Winter/2007_Winter_JAGMAG.pdf\n|format=PDF| title=IA: Life at Guantanamo Bay\n| page=| pages=| publisher=[[Jag Mag]]| author=[[Commander]] [[Daniel Jones (military jurist)|Daniel Jones]]\n| date=Winter 2007| accessdate=2008-02-15\n| quote=Housing is also an interesting topic here. Get used to a loss of privacy and the idea of having a roommate, several in fact. Just hearken back to your childhood and/or college days when you shared everything, labeled your food with your initials, and waited in line to use the bathroom.}}</ref> Four occupants share a two-bedroom cottage.\n\nAccording to [[Commander]] [[Daniel Jones (military jurist)|Daniel Jones]], JTF-GTMO's Staff Judge Advocate:<ref name=JagMagWinter2007/>\n\n<blockquote>The chow here is probably the best I've had and a mainstay of each day's activities. A \"surf and turf\" and special birthday meal are served at least once a month. By the end of your tour in GTMO you'll either weigh 300 pounds or be able to bench press 300 pounds. Nevertheless, you can look forward to a farewell BBQ and presentation of the highly coveted GTMO Bar Association Certificate.</blockquote>\n\n==Commanding officers==\nThe past commanders of JTF-GTMO:<ref name=MiamiHerald2016-11-17/>\n* [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]] (USN), 2019\u2013Present<ref name=Kuehas/>\n*Brigadier General [[John F. Hussey]] (USA), 2019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.southcom.mil/News/PressReleases/Article/1827694/news-release-jtf-gtmo-commanding-officer-relieved-of-duty/ |title=News Release: JTF-GTMO commanding officer relieved of duty |author=SOUTHCOM Public Affairs  |publisher=U.S. Southern Command |date=April 29, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[John C. Ring]] (USN), 2018\u20132019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/press-releases/Article/1496257/joint-task-force-guantanamo-change-of-command-ceremony/ |title=Joint Task Force Guantanamo Change of Command Ceremony |author=JTF GTMO Public Affairs  |publisher=Joint Task Force Guantanamo |date=April 17, 2018 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Edward Cashman (admiral)|Edward B. Cashman]] (USN), 2017\u20132018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/News/Articles/Article/1146117/joint-task-force-guantanamo-welcomes-new-commander/ |title=Joint Task Force Guantanamo Welcomes New Commander |author=JTF GTMO Public Affairs  |publisher=Joint Task Force Guantanamo |date=April 7, 2017 |accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Peter J. Clarke]] (USN), 2015\u20132017<ref>[http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xWEBSITE/command/cdr.html Joint Task Force Guantanamo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408160425/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xWEBSITE/command/cdr.html |date=2016-04-08 }} Joint Task Force Guantanamo Public Affairs, Retrieved April 4, 2016</ref>\n*Brigadier General [[Jose Monteagudo]] (USAF), 2015\n*Rear Admiral [[Kyle Cozad]] (USN), 2014\u20132015\n*Rear Admiral [[Richard W. Butler]] (USN), 2013\u20132014\n*Rear Admiral [[John W. Smith Jr]] (USN), 2012\u20132013\n*Rear Admiral [[David B. Woods]] (USN), 2011\u20132012\n*Rear Admiral [[Jeffrey Harbeson]] (USN), 2010\u20132011\n*Rear Admiral [[Thomas H. Copeman III]] (USN), 2009\u20132010\n*Rear Admiral [[David M. Thomas Jr.]] (USN), 2008\u20132009\n*Rear Admiral [[Mark H. Buzby]] (USN), 2007\u20132008<ref>[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=29615 Buzby Assumes Command of JTF-Guantanamo] US Navy</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Harry B. Harris Jr.]] (USN), 2006\u20132007\n*Brigadier General [[Jay W. Hood]] (USA), 2004\u20132006\n*Major General [[Geoffrey D. Miller]] (USA), 2002\u20132004\n*Major General [[Michael Dunlavey]] (USA), 2002\n*Brigadier General [[Rick Baccus]] (USA), 2002\n*Brigadier General [[Michael Lehnert]] (USMC), 2002\n\n==Task Force motto==\n[[Image:Honor bound -- guantanamo.jpg|thumb|The wall has been painted with part of the motto \"Honor Bound.\"]]\n\nJoint Task Force Guant\u00e1namo's motto is \"Honor Bound to Defend Freedom\" and it was established during the command of [[Geoffrey D. Miller|Army Maj. Gen. Geoffrey Miller]].\n\n==Representation in culture==\n*''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' is the title of a 2004 book by Victoria Brittain (a former [[The Guardian|Guardian]] foreign editor) and [[novelist]] [[Gillian Slovo]] ({{ISBN|1-84002-474-7}}).\n*''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' is the title of a 2004 play, based upon interviews with the families of men detained in Guantanamo Bay, by the same authors. It premiered at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] in London in 2004 and transferred to [[Off Broadway]].<ref name=Timeline>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.timelinetheatre.com/guantanamo/index.htm \n |title=Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom \n |publisher=[[TimeLine Theatre Company]] \n |accessdate=January 15, 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530001432/http://www.timelinetheatre.com/guantanamo/index.htm \n |archivedate=May 30, 2012 \n}}</ref>\n*''[[Good Morning Gitmo]]'' is a one-act comedy written by [[Mishu Hilmy]] and Eric Simon in 2014. The play takes place decades into the future where the guards and staff have been forgotten at [[Camp Delta]]. It was originally produced by The [[Annoyance Theater]] in Chicago, Illinois.<ref name=\"Hayford\">Hayford, Justin [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/good-morning-gitmo/Event?oid=15029124 Review: ''Good Morning Gitmo'']. [[Chicago Reader]]. Retrieved on November 24, 2014.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Wire (JTF-GTMO)]]\n*[[Unlawful combatant]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=MiamiHerald2016-11-17>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article115470333.html\n| title       = Navy sending new commander to run President Trump's Guant\u00e1namo prison\n| publisher   = [[Miami Herald]]\n| author      = [[Carol Rosenberg]]\n| date        = 2016-11-17\n| page        = \n| location    = \n| accessdate  = 2016-11-17\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100423175119/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/ Joint Task Force Guantanamo website]\n\n[[Category:Joint task forces of the United States Armed Forces]]\n[[Category:Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2002]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Joint Task Force Guantanamo\n|image=JTFGTMO logo.png\n|image_size=100px\n|caption=\n|dates= November 2002 - present\n|country= {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America}}}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=Joint\n|type=\n|role=\n|size=\n|command_structure=[[United States Southern Command]]\n|current_commander= [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]]\n|garrison=[[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]]\n|nickname=\n|motto=Honor Bound to Defend Freedom<ref name=TheWireJtfGtmo>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/wire/WirePDF/issue47v8.pdf#15\n| title=Honor Bound to Defend Freedom| page=15| publisher=[[The Wire (JTF-GTMO)]]| author=Carlos Sanchez\n| date=January 17, 2008| accessdate=2008-02-10}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n|identification_symbol=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|notable_commanders=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n}}\n'''Joint Task Force Guantanamo''' ('''JTF-GTMO''') is a [[U.S. military]] [[joint task force]] based at  [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]], [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay, Cuba]] on the southeastern end of the base. JTF-GTMO falls under [[US Southern Command]]. Since January 2002 the command has operated the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s [[Camp X-Ray]] and its successors [[Camp Delta]], Camp V, and Camp Echo, where detained prisoners are held who have been captured in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|the war in Afghanistan]] and elsewhere since the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]. From the command's founding in 2002 to early 2017, the detainee population has been reduced from 779 to 41.<ref name=\"Rosenberg\">{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Carol|date=January 19, 2017|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article127473314.html|title=Obama to leave with 41 captives still at Guant\u00e1namo, blames politics|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref> As of May 2019, the unit is under the command of [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]].<ref name=Kuehas>{{cite web |url=https://www.southcom.mil/News/PressReleases/Article/1836670/news-release-jtf-gtmo-assumption-of-command/ |title=News Release: JTF-GTMO Assumption of Command |author=SOUTHCOM Public Affairs  |publisher=U.S. Southern Command |date=May 4, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{wikisource|Detention, Treatment, and Trial of Certain Non-Citizens in the War Against Terrorism}}\nIn 1992, the United States established [[Operation Sea Signal]] to prepare for a mass migration of refugees from Haiti and Cuba.<ref>JTF-GTMO, [http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg3.pdf Joint Task Force Guantanamo Timeline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308002848/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg3.pdf |date=2010-03-08 }}, accessed May 2010</ref> In 1994, Operation Sea Signal led to the creation of Joint Task Force 160. JTF 160 was responsible for housing and processing more than 40,000 migrants awaiting repatriation or parole to the United States. [[Camp X-Ray]] was established to segregate migrants who had committed crimes, such as theft, assault and battery, prostitution and black-market activities, from other migrants and from U.S. civilians and military personnel at Guantanamo. In 1996, Operation Sea Signal came to an end and the military abandoned Camp X-Ray.\n\nIn December 2001, after the [[September 11 terrorist attacks]] and the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|United States intervention in Afghanistan]], Joint Task Force 160 was reactivated. Camp X-Ray was prepared as a temporary location for the detention of people captured in Afghanistan who were believed to be part of the Taliban or al-Qaeda, neither of which the United States recognized as legal governments. In January 2002, the first [[detainees]] were transferred to Guantanamo Bay and housed in Camp X-Ray. The [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] (ICRC) had its first visit to the facility six days later. The ICRC has continued quarterly visits up to 2010.\n\n==Detention facilities==\nIn April 2002, construction of the new 410-bed [[Camp Delta]] (Camps 1, 2, 3) was completed. The detainees were moved from Camp X-Ray to Camp Delta that month. In November 2002, Joint Task Force 160 and 170 were merged to create Joint Task Force Guantanamo.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nBy 2007 original Camp Delta compound was supplemented by Camps 4, 5 and 6.\n\nCamp 4, opened in February 2003, featured communal style living areas, similar to a military barracks, and was used to house \"compliant\" detainees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2008/us0608/2.htm|title=Locked Up Alone: Detention Conditions and Mental Health at Guantanamo: II. The Range of Prison Facilities at Guantanamo|website=www.hrw.org}}</ref>\n\nCamp 5, opened in May 2004, had segregated housing units (i.e. solitary cells) for detainees who are uncompliant or who pose a threat to other detainees or Joint Task Force staff members.  Camp 5 was closed in 2016 when the total detainee population was reduced to 61.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article100496357.html|title=Guant\u00e1namo downsizes by closing one prison, cutting 400 troops|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCamp 6, opened in November 2006, is patterned after a medium security prison with \"pods\" housing 10 to 20 detainees with individual cells but sharing a common living area.  Camp 6 houses the \"general population\".\n\nAs of late 2016, almost all detainees were housed in Camp 6.\n\n==Status of detainees==\n\nThe status of these detainees is disputed. The [[United States]] government defines them as [[enemy combatant]]s, claiming their status was not that of a [[prisoner of war]] as recognized under the [[Geneva Conventions]] (due to not being affiliated with any government, being alleged members of [[Al Qaida]] or groups affiliated with them).\n\nIn ''[[Rasul v Bush]]'' (2004), the Supreme Court held that the detainees had the right to counsel and to challenge their detentions at an impartial tribunal, according to ''habeas corpus''. On June 29, 2006, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in  ''[[Hamdan v. Rumsfeld]]'' that they had the minimal protection of [[Wikisource:Third Geneva Convention#Article 3|Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions]] in that detainees must be housed and treated humanely, and that they had the right to an impartial tribunal to hear charges against them. It said the military tribunals as established by the Dept. of Defense did not have sufficient authority, and Congress needed to authorize any system outside the established US civil and military justice systems.\n<!--Other parties{{Who|date=January 2008}} insist that the captives be granted full [[prisoner of war]] rights and privileges listed in the Geneva Convention.-->In ''[[Boumediene v. Bush]]'' (2008), the Supreme Court held that the detainees' right to ''habeas corpus'' could not be taken away by the [[Military Commission Act of 2006]], which they ruled was unconstitutional. In addition, the Supreme Court held that detainees had the right to access federal courts to hear their ''[[habeas corpus]]'' challenges. Some of the cases are proceeding through the federal court system.\n\n==Intelligence task forces==\nIn February 2002, Joint Task Force 170 was created as the intelligence task force to work side by side with Joint Task Force 160.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}  At a later date, JTF 170 was re-designated as the Joint Intelligence Group and was assigned as a subordinate element of Joint Task Force Guantanamo.  The other subordinate elements of JTF GTMO are the Joint Detention Group and the Joint Medical Group.\n\n==Joint Detention Group==\nThe Joint Detention Group is one of the components of the Task Force. It is the organization assigned to guarding the captives, and maintaining camp security.<ref name=BrochureJDG>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg6.pdf\n |title       = Detainee operations\n |publisher   = Joint Task Force Guantanamo\n |year        = 2009\n |accessdate  = 2010-01-22\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100308002639/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/index/JTFGBrochurePg6.pdf\n |archivedate = 2010-03-08\n}}</ref>\nThe guards within the Joint Detention Group come from the [[United States Army]], [[United States Navy]], and other [[United States Armed Services]].\n\nIn 2009, guards outnumbered prisoners in Guantanamo by more than five to one.\n\nThe officers commanding the Joint Detention Group, also known as the warden, have included:\n*[[Colonel]] [[Adolph McQueen]], 2002<ref name=BostonGlobe2002>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2003/09/14/detainees_in_cuba_get_appetizing_incentives/| title=Detainees in Cuba get appetizing incentives| publisher=[[Boston Globe]]| date=2003-09-14| author=Dan Fesperman }}</ref>\n*Colonel [[Michael Bumgarner]], 2006\n*Colonel [[Bruce Vargo]], 2008-2010\n*Colonel [[Donnie Thomas (US Army)|Donnie Thomas]], 2010-2012\n*Colonel [[John Bogdan]], 2012-2014<ref name=Jtf-Gtmo2012-06-08>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xwebsite/print/stories/2012/06June/02JDG.html\n |title       = Warrior Six Signing Off\n |publisher   = [[JTF Guantanamo Public Affairs]]\n |author      = Lewis Hilburn\n |date        = 2012-06-02\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil%2Fxwebsite%2Fprint%2Fstories%2F2012%2F06June%2F02JDG.html&date=2013-03-24\n |archivedate = 2013-03-24\n}}</ref>\n*Colonel David Heath, 2014-2016<ref>[http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/News/Articles/Article/1063567/joint-detention-group-change-of-command/ Joint Detention Group Change of Command] JTF GTMO Public Affairs. July 1, 2016</ref>\n*Colonel Stephen Gabavics, 2016-2018\n*Colonel Steven Yamashita 2018-Present\n\n==Living quarters==\nEnlisted personnel live in pre-fabicated quarters, similar to shipping containers.<ref name=AFPSEnlisted20050225>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25798\n| title=Guantanamo Troops Deployed in Unusual Surroundings\n| publisher=[[American Forces Press Service]]\n| author=[[:s:Kathleen Rhem|Kathleen T. Rhem]]\n| date=February 25, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-25\n| quote=Living conditions vary considerably within the JTF. Enlisted service members generally live in prefabricated individual buildings, which they call \"houses\" with a touch of cynicism. The shipping-container-like quarters each house four to six servicemembers. The troops typically divide the space as evenly as possible and then partition \"rooms\" by hanging blankets and shower curtains.\n}}</ref> Each prefab unit houses four to six personnel.  Each prefab unit ships with a toilet and sink, but no internal partitions. Occupants are allowed to erect curtains to make temporary partitions, for privacy. Occupants share communal showers, shared between prefab quarters.\n\nOfficers and senior non-commissioned officers typically share cottages left over from family residences that were constructed when the base had a larger permanent population.<ref name=AFPSOfficers20050225>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=25798\n| title=Guantanamo Troops Deployed in Unusual Surroundings\n| publisher=[[American Forces Press Service]]\n| author=[[:s:Kathleen Rhem|Kathleen T. Rhem]]\n| date=February 25, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-25\n| quote=Senior enlisted members and officers generally live in converted Navy family housing left over from when the base housed a larger population of permanent-party personnel. For instance, one two-bedroom apartment might be assigned to four junior officers.\n}}</ref><ref name=JagMagWinter2007>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.jag.navy.mil/news/jag_mag/archive/2007_Winter/2007_Winter_JAGMAG.pdf\n|format=PDF| title=IA: Life at Guantanamo Bay\n| page=| pages=| publisher=[[Jag Mag]]| author=[[Commander]] [[Daniel Jones (military jurist)|Daniel Jones]]\n| date=Winter 2007| accessdate=2008-02-15\n| quote=Housing is also an interesting topic here. Get used to a loss of privacy and the idea of having a roommate, several in fact. Just hearken back to your childhood and/or college days when you shared everything, labeled your food with your initials, and waited in line to use the bathroom.}}</ref> Four occupants share a two-bedroom cottage.\n\nAccording to [[Commander]] [[Daniel Jones (military jurist)|Daniel Jones]], JTF-GTMO's Staff Judge Advocate:<ref name=JagMagWinter2007/>\n\n<blockquote>The chow here is probably the best I've had and a mainstay of each day's activities. A \"surf and turf\" and special birthday meal are served at least once a month. By the end of your tour in GTMO you'll either weigh 300 pounds or be able to bench press 300 pounds. Nevertheless, you can look forward to a farewell BBQ and presentation of the highly coveted GTMO Bar Association Certificate.</blockquote>\n\n==Commanding officers==\nThe past commanders of JTF-GTMO:<ref name=MiamiHerald2016-11-17/>\n* [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Timothy C. Kuehhas]] (USN), 2019-Present<ref name=Kuehas/>\n*Brigadier General [[John F. Hussey]] (USA), 2019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.southcom.mil/News/PressReleases/Article/1827694/news-release-jtf-gtmo-commanding-officer-relieved-of-duty/ |title=News Release: JTF-GTMO commanding officer relieved of duty |author=SOUTHCOM Public Affairs  |publisher=U.S. Southern Command |date=April 29, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[John C. Ring]] (USN), 2018-2019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/press-releases/Article/1496257/joint-task-force-guantanamo-change-of-command-ceremony/ |title=Joint Task Force Guantanamo Change of Command Ceremony |author=JTF GTMO Public Affairs  |publisher=Joint Task Force Guantanamo |date=April 17, 2018 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Edward Cashman (admiral)|Edward B. Cashman]] (USN), 2017-2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/News/Articles/Article/1146117/joint-task-force-guantanamo-welcomes-new-commander/ |title=Joint Task Force Guantanamo Welcomes New Commander |author=JTF GTMO Public Affairs  |publisher=Joint Task Force Guantanamo |date=April 7, 2017 |accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Peter J. Clarke]] (USN), 2015-2017<ref>[http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xWEBSITE/command/cdr.html Joint Task Force Guantanamo] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408160425/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/xWEBSITE/command/cdr.html |date=2016-04-08 }} Joint Task Force Guantanamo Public Affairs, Retrieved April 4, 2016</ref>\n*Brigadier General [[Jose Monteagudo]] (USAF), 2015\n*Rear Admiral [[Kyle Cozad]] (USN), 2014-2015\n*Rear Admiral [[Richard W. Butler]] (USN), 2013-2014\n*Rear Admiral [[John W. Smith Jr]] (USN), 2012-2013\n*Rear Admiral [[David B. Woods]] (USN), 2011-2012\n*Rear Admiral [[Jeffrey Harbeson]] (USN), 2010-2011\n*Rear Admiral [[Thomas H. Copeman III]] (USN), 2009-2010\n*Rear Admiral [[David M. Thomas Jr.]] (USN), 2008-2009\n*Rear Admiral [[Mark H. Buzby]] (USN), 2007-2008<ref>[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=29615 Buzby Assumes Command of JTF-Guantanamo] US Navy</ref>\n*Rear Admiral [[Harry B. Harris Jr.]] (USN), 2006-2007\n*Brigadier General [[Jay W. Hood]] (USA), 2004-2006\n*Major General [[Geoffrey D. Miller]] (USA), 2002-2004\n*Major General [[Michael Dunlavey]] (USA), 2002\n*Brigadier General [[Rick Baccus]] (USA), 2002\n*Brigadier General [[Michael Lehnert]] (USMC), 2002\n\n==Task Force motto==\n[[Image:Honor bound -- guantanamo.jpg|thumb|The wall has been painted with part of the motto \"Honor Bound.\"]]\n\nJoint Task Force Guant\u00e1namo's motto is \"Honor Bound to Defend Freedom\" and it was established during the command of [[Geoffrey D. Miller|Army Maj. Gen. Geoffrey Miller]].\n\n==Representation in culture==\n*''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' is the title of a 2004 book by Victoria Brittain (a former [[The Guardian|Guardian]] foreign editor) and [[novelist]] [[Gillian Slovo]] ({{ISBN|1-84002-474-7}}).\n*''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' is the title of a 2004 play, based upon interviews with the families of men detained in Guantanamo Bay, by the same authors. It premiered at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] in London in 2004 and transferred to [[Off Broadway]].<ref name=Timeline>\n{{cite news\n |url=http://www.timelinetheatre.com/guantanamo/index.htm \n |title=Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom \n |publisher=[[TimeLine Theatre Company]] \n |accessdate=January 15, 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530001432/http://www.timelinetheatre.com/guantanamo/index.htm \n |archivedate=May 30, 2012 \n}}</ref>\n*''[[Good Morning Gitmo]]'' is a one-act comedy written by [[Mishu Hilmy]] and Eric Simon in 2014. The play takes place decades into the future where the guards and staff have been forgotten at [[Camp Delta]]. It was originally produced by The [[Annoyance Theater]] in Chicago, Illinois.<ref name=\"Hayford\">Hayford, Justin [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/good-morning-gitmo/Event?oid=15029124 Review: ''Good Morning Gitmo'']. [[Chicago Reader]]. Retrieved on November 24, 2014.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Wire (JTF-GTMO)]]\n*[[Unlawful combatant]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=MiamiHerald2016-11-17>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/guantanamo/article115470333.html\n| title       = Navy sending new commander to run President Trump's Guant\u00e1namo prison\n| publisher   = [[Miami Herald]]\n| author      = [[Carol Rosenberg]]\n| date        = 2016-11-17\n| page        = \n| location    = \n| accessdate  = 2016-11-17\n| quote       = \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100423175119/http://www.jtfgtmo.southcom.mil/ Joint Task Force Guantanamo website]\n\n[[Category:Joint task forces of the United States Armed Forces]]\n[[Category:Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2002]]\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Task_Force_Guantanamo"}
{"title_page": "Kindred of the East", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=August 2014}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox game\n|title=''Kindred of the East''\n|image=KindredOTE_cover.jpg\n|caption=Cover art\n|designer= [[Robert Hatch]]\n|publisher= [[White Wolf Publishing]]\n|date= February 1998\n|genre= Personal [[Horror fiction|horror]]\n|system= [[Storyteller System]]\n}}\n'''''Kindred of the East''''' is a [[tabletop role-playing game]] supplement by [[White Wolf Publishing]] for their ''[[Vampire: The Masquerade]]'' line. The vanguard of White Wolf's \"Year of the Lotus\" theme (which created \"Eastern\" counterparts to all of their major product lines in the [[World of Darkness]]), this sourcebook is a stand-alone setting, requiring only secondary rules to be fully playable. The setting spans [[Asia]], allowing players to play the so-called Kindred of the East, [[vampire]]s of [[Asia]].\n\n==History==\n''Kindred of the East'' was published by [[White Wolf Publishing]] in February 1998 as the first and main entry in their ''Year of the Lotus'' series,<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\"/><ref name=\"designers\"/> a line of Asia-themed books based on White Wolf's ''[[World of Darkness]]'' games. ''Kindred of the East'' was based on ''[[Vampire: The Masquerade]]'', and was published as a supplement that required the ''Vampire'' rulebook to be played, following the model of the publisher's ''[[Mummy: The Resurrection|Mummy Second Edition]]'' from the year prior. This was done as the game could attract attention in the same way as a new standalone game, while not being the start of a new line that would require support.<ref name=\"designers\">{{cite book |last=Appelcline |first=Shannon |year=2014 |title=Designers & Dragons: The '90s |edition=2nd |publisher=Evil Hat Productions |pages=7\u201352 |isbn=978-1-613170-84-7}}</ref>\n\nThe game did however receive a series of supplements on its own, starting with the ''Kindred of the East Companion'' book in 1999, which updated the game to bring it in line with 1998's ''Revised Edition'' of ''Vampire: The Masquerade'', as well as further detailing Asian vampire society and adding new gameplay mechanics and background information.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lhomme |first=Tristan |date=June\u2013July 1999 |title=Kindred of the East Companion |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=120 |page=84 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref> As part of ''[[Time of Judgment]]'' event, the ending to the ''World of Darkness'' series, White Wolf concluded the ''Kindred of the East'' metaplot with adventures published in the book ''World of Darkness: Time of Judgment''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>\n\n==Overview==\nCharacters in Kindred of the East (or Kuei-jin, as they call themselves) are [[vampire]]s as depicted in classical [[Japanese mythology|Japanese]], [[Chinese mythology|Chinese]], and [[India]]n [[Hindu mythology|Hindu]], [[Taoist]], [[Shinto]] and [[Buddhist]] [[mythology]]. Unlike the vampires traditionally associated with [[Dracula]] or Caine, Kuei-jin were once mortals who died with the burden of unfulfilled [[Dharma]] or duties. Tortured in [[Yomi]] for their inadequacies in life, their [[soul]]s successfully escaped and returned to their bodies. Now half-alive and half-dead, Kuei-jin must live by stealing [[Qi|chi]] from mortal victims to sustain themselves while trying to fulfill their Dharma. The most convenient form of chi that can be stolen is in blood, leading to their vampiric tendencies, but they cannot create new vampires. Practically all Kindred distrust the Kuei-jin. The Kuei-jin are also known to war with the other sects for territory.\n\n==Themes==\nKuei-jin are beings torn by inner conflict, and the themes of the game relate to this heavily.  Unlike Western vampires, Kuei-jin are [[ghost|revenant]]s and thus spiritual beings in nature.\n\n===Yin vs. Yang===\nThe classic opposition of [[Yin Yang|yin and yang]] are important to Kuei-jin not only for philosophical reasons, but because this dichotomy also delineates the two forms of chi they can potentially ingest. An imbalance of yin or yang chi in their system can lead to dire consequences.  Yin-imbalanced Kuei-jin become corpselike [[zombie]]s suffering from a lack of [[emotion]]. At its worst, yin-imbalance reduces a kuei-jin to a [[hopping corpse]]. Yang-imbalanced Kuei-jin suffer wild mood swings and impulsive lusts for food, sex, and other forms of stimulation. Possibly the strangest consequence of yang-imbalance is the ability to have or sire children. Such children are called [[Dhampir (World of Darkness)|dhampyr]]s, and are mortal half-vampires.\n\n===Hun vs. P'o===\nA Kuei-jin's stint in the hells of [[Yomi]] divides the mind into two [[Hun and po]] parts: The Hun, or high mind, that is the seat of rational thought, and the P'o, or demon mind, that exists to satisfy its own base urges (usually at the expense of the Hun). As former [[Wraith: The Oblivion|wraiths]], a Kuei-jin has a splinter of the forces of Oblivion in its soul. While many Kuei-jin see their P'o as a curse, it is important to note that without the P'o, they would never have escaped hell in the first place. Furthermore, Kuei-jin who stifle and contain their P'o utterly become cold, calculating individuals who lack any ideological spark; such stagnancy can be devastating when the weight of karma (spiritual consequences of actions) is on one's shoulders.\n\n===Mortal vs. Spirit===\nThe Kuei-jin stand between the mortal world (which they can never fully return to) and the spirit world (which they cannot fully embrace). Many Kuei-jin struggle to find a balance between these two worlds that suits the precise nature of their Dharma.\n\n==Dharmas==\nA Kuei-jin's existence is a quest for enlightenment. In their search for karmic resolution, different Kuei-jin follow different paths to ease their karmic discomfort. The Dharmas, five philosophies accepted by the greater Kuei-jin community as potential paths, each emphasize a particular aspect of Kuei-jin existence:\n\n* '''The Howl of the Devil Tiger''': The Dharma embracing the P'o; these Kuei-Jin seek to metamorphose into demons (rather than to serve demons, as the hated Akuma do).\n* '''The Way of the Resplendent Crane''': The Dharma embracing the Hun; they seek to uphold the highest principles (in theory; they are nonetheless still monsters).\n* '''The Song of the Shadow''': The Dharma embracing Yin. Embrace their dead and passionless nature through the pursuit of knowledge and sorcerous power, seeking mastery over the forces of death.\n* '''The Path of a Thousand Whispers''': The Dharma embracing balance. Known also as \"Rootless Trees\", they adopt a series of different mortal identities in order to learn from a variety of experiences, while their true self remains detached and \"Zen\" about these lessons.\n* '''The Dance of the Thrashing Dragon''': The Dharma embracing Yang. Seek to defy their undead state through frenzied revelry and acts meant to celebrate life (in all its bloodcurdling savagery).\n\nIn addition to these primary dharmas, a number of Heretical Dharmas have also come into existence. Not accepted in Kuei-jin society, these paths nevertheless find some followers:\n\n* '''The Face of the Gods''': A Dharma embracing both Hun and P'o. As the name suggests, they intend to become literal gods on Earth, or at least claim the role and be worshipped.\n* '''The Flame of the Rising Phoenix''': A Dharma embracing both Hun and Yang, whose members seek to reclaim their original lives rather than to accept their new status as monsters.\n* '''The Spirit of the Living Earth''': A Dharma embracing both Yin and Yang. A shamanic path devoted to the Old Ways.\n* '''The Tempest of Inner Focus''': A Dharma embracing balance, in a more straightforward and moderate manner than the Thousand Whispers. Influenced by Taoism.\n* '''The Scorpion Eaters''': A Dharma embracing the P'o, who can consume only Tainted Chi and yet are not Akuma. \n\nFinally, some Kuei-jin turn their backs on enlightenment entirely, instead swearing fealty to the Yama Kings (the rulers of Yomi) to metamorphose into Akuma, the demon people. Bartering their souls, Akuma enter [[Faust]]ian deals with the Yama Kings and pursue only power.\n\n==The Middle Kingdom==\nKuei-jin are the most visible shen (supernatural creatures) of the Middle Kingdom (modern [[Asia]]), but are not alone. Unlike [[Vampire: The Masquerade|Western Kindred]], they have close ties with the spirit world. They must also compete with the hengeyokai ([[Changing Breed|Shapeshifters]] of the East), [[Mage: The Ascension|mages]], and [[Preta|gaki]].\n\nThere are several offshoots of the Kuei-Jin who share a measure of their condition but are different in certain particulars.\n\u00a7 Dhampyrs are the half-dead mortal children sired (or, more unusually, borne) by Kuei-Jin in the throes of Yang imbalance, which enables them to breed as if living. Capable of controlling Chi and manifesting Disciplines, the dhampyrs have many of the vampires' strengths and few of their weaknesses, both to a milder extent.\n\u00a7 Yulan-Jin are a subset of Kuei-Jin whose souls are not able to reform their original bodies after escaping from Hell; instead, they possess the bodies of the recently dead, and when \"killed\", they must find a new corpse to inhabit, forcing them to switch identities. Are generally scorned by the Kuei-Jin for their perceived spiritual weakness.\n\n==Books==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Title !! Product No. !!ISBN !! Release !! Note\n|-\n|''Kindred of the East'' || WW2900 || {{ISBN|1-56504-232-8}} || February 1998<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\"/> || Core rulebook\n|-\n|''Kindred of the East Companion'' || WW2901 || {{ISBN|1-56504-223-9}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\">{{cite magazine |date=June\u2013July 1999 |title=White Wolf |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=120 |page=84 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref>  || Updates the game for ''Vampire: The Masquerade Revised Edition'', adds mechanics and background information<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\"/>\n|-\n|''The 1000 Hells'' || WW2902 || {{ISBN|1-56504-226-3}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\"/>  || \n|-\n|''Shadow War'' || WW2903 || {{ISBN|1-56504-227-1}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 122 ww news\">{{cite magazine |date=October\u2013November 1999 |title=White Wolf |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=122 |pages=88\u201390 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref> || Details warfare between Kuei-jin<ref name=\"casusbelli 122 ww news\"/>\n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Devil-Tigers'' || WW2904 || {{ISBN|1-56504-239-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Bone Flowers'' || WW2905 || {{ISBN|1-56504-240-9}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Thousand Whispers'' || WW2906 || {{ISBN|1-58846-200-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Thrashing Dragons'' || WW2907 || {{ISBN|1-58846-211-0}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Resplendent Cranes'' || WW2908 || {{ISBN|1-58846-221-8}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Half-Damned: Dhampyr'' || WW2920 || {{ISBN|1-56504-247-6}} ||  || \n|-\n|''San Francisco by Night'' || WW2921 || {{ISBN|1-58846-231-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Heresies of the Way'' || WW2922 || {{ISBN|1-58846-232-3}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Killing Streets'' || WW2930 || {{ISBN|1-58846-208-0}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Blood & Silk'' || WW2935 || {{ISBN|1-56504-242-5}} || || A sourcebook set in the ''[[Vampire: The Dark Ages]]'' historical setting\n|-\n|''Sunset Empires'' || WW9238  || {{ISBN|1-58846-233-1}} ||  || Originally only sold in an electronic format, the book entered [[DriveThru]]'s [[Print on Demand]] service\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n''Sci-Fi Universe'' was positive to the game, calling it well researched and fascinating, and facilitating a lot of new ideas for adventures.<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\">{{cite magazine |last=Honigsberg |first=David |date=April 1998 |title=Kindred of the East |url=https://archive.org/details/Sci-Fi_Universe_v04n01_1998-04/page/n25 |magazine=Sci-Fi Universe |issue=3 |page=27 |publisher=Sovereign Media}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030212071745/http://www.white-wolf.com/Games/Pages/KotEHome.html |date=February 12, 2003 |title=Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130925143645/http://wiki.white-wolf.com/worldofdarkness/index.php?title=Kindred_of_the_East Kindred of the East] in [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517043916/http://wiki.white-wolf.com/worldofdarkness/ The official World of Darkness wiki]\n\n{{World of Darkness}}\n\n[[Category:Vampire: The Masquerade]]\n[[Category:Role-playing games introduced in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2014}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox game\n|title=''Kindred of the East''\n|image=KindredOTE_cover.jpg\n|caption=Cover art\n|designer= [[Robert Hatch (game designer)|Robert Hatch]]\n|publisher= [[White Wolf Publishing]]\n|date= February 1998\n|genre= Personal [[Horror fiction|horror]]\n|system= [[Storyteller System]]\n}}\n'''''Kindred of the East''''' is a [[tabletop role-playing game]] supplement by [[White Wolf Publishing]] for their ''[[Vampire: The Masquerade]]'' line. The vanguard of White Wolf's \"Year of the Lotus\" theme (which created \"Eastern\" counterparts to all of their major product lines in the [[World of Darkness]]), this sourcebook is a stand-alone setting, requiring only secondary rules to be fully playable. The setting spans [[Asia]], allowing players to play the so-called Kindred of the East, [[vampire]]s of [[Asia]].\n\n==History==\n''Kindred of the East'' was published by [[White Wolf Publishing]] in February 1998 as the first and main entry in their ''Year of the Lotus'' series,<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\"/><ref name=\"designers\"/> a line of Asia-themed books based on White Wolf's ''[[World of Darkness]]'' games. ''Kindred of the East'' was based on ''[[Vampire: The Masquerade]]'', and was published as a supplement that required the ''Vampire'' rulebook to be played, following the model of the publisher's ''[[Mummy: The Resurrection|Mummy Second Edition]]'' from the year prior. This was done as the game could attract attention in the same way as a new standalone game, while not being the start of a new line that would require support.<ref name=\"designers\">{{cite book |last=Appelcline |first=Shannon |year=2014 |title=Designers & Dragons: The '90s |edition=2nd |publisher=Evil Hat Productions |pages=7\u201352 |isbn=978-1-613170-84-7}}</ref>\n\nThe game did however receive a series of supplements on its own, starting with the ''Kindred of the East Companion'' book in 1999, which updated the game to bring it in line with 1998's ''Revised Edition'' of ''Vampire: The Masquerade'', as well as further detailing Asian vampire society and adding new gameplay mechanics and background information.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lhomme |first=Tristan |date=June\u2013July 1999 |title=Kindred of the East Companion |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=120 |page=84 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref> As part of ''[[Time of Judgment]]'' event, the ending to the ''World of Darkness'' series, White Wolf concluded the ''Kindred of the East'' metaplot with adventures published in the book ''World of Darkness: Time of Judgment''.<ref name=\"designers\"/>\n\n==Overview==\nCharacters in Kindred of the East (or Kuei-jin, as they call themselves) are [[vampire]]s as depicted in classical [[Japanese mythology|Japanese]], [[Chinese mythology|Chinese]], and [[India]]n [[Hindu mythology|Hindu]], [[Taoist]], [[Shinto]] and [[Buddhist]] [[mythology]]. Unlike the vampires traditionally associated with [[Dracula]] or Caine, Kuei-jin were once mortals who died with the burden of unfulfilled [[Dharma]] or duties. Tortured in [[Yomi]] for their inadequacies in life, their [[soul]]s successfully escaped and returned to their bodies. Now half-alive and half-dead, Kuei-jin must live by stealing [[Qi|chi]] from mortal victims to sustain themselves while trying to fulfill their Dharma. The most convenient form of chi that can be stolen is in blood, leading to their vampiric tendencies, but they cannot create new vampires. Practically all Kindred distrust the Kuei-jin. The Kuei-jin are also known to war with the other sects for territory.\n\n==Themes==\nKuei-jin are beings torn by inner conflict, and the themes of the game relate to this heavily.  Unlike Western vampires, Kuei-jin are [[ghost|revenant]]s and thus spiritual beings in nature.\n\n===Yin vs. Yang===\nThe classic opposition of [[Yin Yang|yin and yang]] are important to Kuei-jin not only for philosophical reasons, but because this dichotomy also delineates the two forms of chi they can potentially ingest. An imbalance of yin or yang chi in their system can lead to dire consequences.  Yin-imbalanced Kuei-jin become corpselike [[zombie]]s suffering from a lack of [[emotion]]. At its worst, yin-imbalance reduces a kuei-jin to a [[hopping corpse]]. Yang-imbalanced Kuei-jin suffer wild mood swings and impulsive lusts for food, sex, and other forms of stimulation. Possibly the strangest consequence of yang-imbalance is the ability to have or sire children. Such children are called [[Dhampir (World of Darkness)|dhampyr]]s, and are mortal half-vampires.\n\n===Hun vs. P'o===\nA Kuei-jin's stint in the hells of [[Yomi]] divides the mind into two [[Hun and po]] parts: The Hun, or high mind, that is the seat of rational thought, and the P'o, or demon mind, that exists to satisfy its own base urges (usually at the expense of the Hun). As former [[Wraith: The Oblivion|wraiths]], a Kuei-jin has a splinter of the forces of Oblivion in its soul. While many Kuei-jin see their P'o as a curse, it is important to note that without the P'o, they would never have escaped hell in the first place. Furthermore, Kuei-jin who stifle and contain their P'o utterly become cold, calculating individuals who lack any ideological spark; such stagnancy can be devastating when the weight of karma (spiritual consequences of actions) is on one's shoulders.\n\n===Mortal vs. Spirit===\nThe Kuei-jin stand between the mortal world (which they can never fully return to) and the spirit world (which they cannot fully embrace). Many Kuei-jin struggle to find a balance between these two worlds that suits the precise nature of their Dharma.\n\n==Dharmas==\nA Kuei-jin's existence is a quest for enlightenment. In their search for karmic resolution, different Kuei-jin follow different paths to ease their karmic discomfort. The Dharmas, five philosophies accepted by the greater Kuei-jin community as potential paths, each emphasize a particular aspect of Kuei-jin existence:\n\n* '''The Howl of the Devil Tiger''': The Dharma embracing the P'o; these Kuei-Jin seek to metamorphose into demons (rather than to serve demons, as the hated Akuma do).\n* '''The Way of the Resplendent Crane''': The Dharma embracing the Hun; they seek to uphold the highest principles (in theory; they are nonetheless still monsters).\n* '''The Song of the Shadow''': The Dharma embracing Yin. Embrace their dead and passionless nature through the pursuit of knowledge and sorcerous power, seeking mastery over the forces of death.\n* '''The Path of a Thousand Whispers''': The Dharma embracing balance. Known also as \"Rootless Trees\", they adopt a series of different mortal identities in order to learn from a variety of experiences, while their true self remains detached and \"Zen\" about these lessons.\n* '''The Dance of the Thrashing Dragon''': The Dharma embracing Yang. Seek to defy their undead state through frenzied revelry and acts meant to celebrate life (in all its bloodcurdling savagery).\n\nIn addition to these primary dharmas, a number of Heretical Dharmas have also come into existence. Not accepted in Kuei-jin society, these paths nevertheless find some followers:\n\n* '''The Face of the Gods''': A Dharma embracing both Hun and P'o. As the name suggests, they intend to become literal gods on Earth, or at least claim the role and be worshipped.\n* '''The Flame of the Rising Phoenix''': A Dharma embracing both Hun and Yang, whose members seek to reclaim their original lives rather than to accept their new status as monsters.\n* '''The Spirit of the Living Earth''': A Dharma embracing both Yin and Yang. A shamanic path devoted to the Old Ways.\n* '''The Tempest of Inner Focus''': A Dharma embracing balance, in a more straightforward and moderate manner than the Thousand Whispers. Influenced by Taoism.\n* '''The Scorpion Eaters''': A Dharma embracing the P'o, who can consume only Tainted Chi and yet are not Akuma. \n\nFinally, some Kuei-jin turn their backs on enlightenment entirely, instead swearing fealty to the Yama Kings (the rulers of Yomi) to metamorphose into Akuma, the demon people. Bartering their souls, Akuma enter [[Faust]]ian deals with the Yama Kings and pursue only power.\n\n==The Middle Kingdom==\nKuei-jin are the most visible shen (supernatural creatures) of the Middle Kingdom (modern [[Asia]]), but are not alone. Unlike [[Vampire: The Masquerade|Western Kindred]], they have close ties with the spirit world. They must also compete with the hengeyokai ([[Changing Breed|Shapeshifters]] of the East), [[Mage: The Ascension|mages]], and [[Preta|gaki]].\n\nThere are several offshoots of the Kuei-Jin who share a measure of their condition but are different in certain particulars.\n\u00a7 Dhampyrs are the half-dead mortal children sired (or, more unusually, borne) by Kuei-Jin in the throes of Yang imbalance, which enables them to breed as if living. Capable of controlling Chi and manifesting Disciplines, the dhampyrs have many of the vampires' strengths and few of their weaknesses, both to a milder extent.\n\u00a7 Yulan-Jin are a subset of Kuei-Jin whose souls are not able to reform their original bodies after escaping from Hell; instead, they possess the bodies of the recently dead, and when \"killed\", they must find a new corpse to inhabit, forcing them to switch identities. Are generally scorned by the Kuei-Jin for their perceived spiritual weakness.\n\n==Books==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Title !! Product No. !!ISBN !! Release !! Note\n|-\n|''Kindred of the East'' || WW2900 || {{ISBN|1-56504-232-8}} || February 1998<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\"/> || Core rulebook\n|-\n|''Kindred of the East Companion'' || WW2901 || {{ISBN|1-56504-223-9}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\">{{cite magazine |date=June\u2013July 1999 |title=White Wolf |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=120 |page=84 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref>  || Updates the game for ''Vampire: The Masquerade Revised Edition'', adds mechanics and background information<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\"/>\n|-\n|''The 1000 Hells'' || WW2902 || {{ISBN|1-56504-226-3}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 120 ww news\"/>  || \n|-\n|''Shadow War'' || WW2903 || {{ISBN|1-56504-227-1}} || 1999<ref name=\"casusbelli 122 ww news\">{{cite magazine |date=October\u2013November 1999 |title=White Wolf |language=French |magazine=[[Casus Belli (magazine)|Casus Belli]] |issue=122 |pages=88\u201390 |publisher=Excelsior Publications}}</ref> || Details warfare between Kuei-jin<ref name=\"casusbelli 122 ww news\"/>\n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Devil-Tigers'' || WW2904 || {{ISBN|1-56504-239-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Bone Flowers'' || WW2905 || {{ISBN|1-56504-240-9}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Thousand Whispers'' || WW2906 || {{ISBN|1-58846-200-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Thrashing Dragons'' || WW2907 || {{ISBN|1-58846-211-0}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Dharma Book: Resplendent Cranes'' || WW2908 || {{ISBN|1-58846-221-8}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Half-Damned: Dhampyr'' || WW2920 || {{ISBN|1-56504-247-6}} ||  || \n|-\n|''San Francisco by Night'' || WW2921 || {{ISBN|1-58846-231-5}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Heresies of the Way'' || WW2922 || {{ISBN|1-58846-232-3}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Killing Streets'' || WW2930 || {{ISBN|1-58846-208-0}} ||  || \n|-\n|''Blood & Silk'' || WW2935 || {{ISBN|1-56504-242-5}} || || A sourcebook set in the ''[[Vampire: The Dark Ages]]'' historical setting\n|-\n|''Sunset Empires'' || WW9238  || {{ISBN|1-58846-233-1}} ||  || Originally only sold in an electronic format, the book entered [[DriveThru]]'s [[Print on Demand]] service\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n''Sci-Fi Universe'' was positive to the game, calling it well researched and fascinating, and facilitating a lot of new ideas for adventures.<ref name=\"scifiuni 1998-04\">{{cite magazine |last=Honigsberg |first=David |date=April 1998 |title=Kindred of the East |url=https://archive.org/details/Sci-Fi_Universe_v04n01_1998-04/page/n25 |magazine=Sci-Fi Universe |issue=3 |page=27 |publisher=Sovereign Media}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030212071745/http://www.white-wolf.com/Games/Pages/KotEHome.html |date=February 12, 2003 |title=Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130925143645/http://wiki.white-wolf.com/worldofdarkness/index.php?title=Kindred_of_the_East Kindred of the East] in [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517043916/http://wiki.white-wolf.com/worldofdarkness/ The official World of Darkness wiki]\n\n{{World of Darkness}}\n\n[[Category:Vampire: The Masquerade]]\n[[Category:Role-playing games introduced in 1998]]\n", "name_user": "Alexandra IDV", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kindred_of_the_East"}
{"title_page": "Stuck with Hackett", "text_new": "{{short description|Television series}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2011}}<!-- addressed advert issues -->\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Stuck with Hackett\n| image              = Hackett setting up engine.jpg\n| genre              = [[Documentary]]<br/>[[Science]]\n| creator            = [[Nathaniel Grouille]] <br/> [[Korelan Cone]]\n| starring           = Chris Hackett\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 1\n| num_episodes       = 9\n| runtime            = 30 minutes\n| distributor        = [[Science Channel]]\n| network            = [[Science Channel]]\n| first_run          = United States\n| first_aired        = {{start date|2011|8|18}}\n}}\n'''''Stuck with Hackett''''' is a television show created and produced by [[Silver Machine]] for the [[Science Channel]].  It was commissioned as a pilot in 2010 and picked up as a nine-part series which began airing on August 18, 2011.  It follows the trials and tribulations of artist [[Chris Hackett (artist)|Chris Hackett]], founder of the [[Madagascar Institute]] as he turns everyday trash, into new and unexpected machines or mechanisms.\n\n== Format ==\nEach episode takes Hackett to a different abandoned location. In season one, Hackett visits a variety of places, including a rail yard, a munitions factory, and a log cabin.  After deciding what he\u2019s going to create to make his stay in the abandoned location more enjoyable, Hackett begins to collect various pieces of \"obtainium\",<ref name=\"MLM\">{{cite web\n |title='Stuck With Hackett,' and such a find\n |first=Tom \n |last=Conroy\n |date=August 18 \u2013 October 13, 2011\n |work=[[Media Life Magazine]]\n |url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reviews_21/-Stuck-With-Hackett-and-such-a-find.asp\n}}</ref> a term he uses for anything from trash to scrap metal to large pieces of machinery that are being repurposed. Hackett then proceeds to construct the desired completed object, with \"off camera support\" of his production team.<ref name=\"MLM\"/>\n\n== Chris Hackett ==\n[[Chris Hackett (artist)|Chris Hackett]] is an artist who grew up in New York. He creates large, interactive art installations. He is the founder of The Madagascar Institute, an artist cooperative space based in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{cite web | title=Up Close With the Madagascar Institute's Pulse-Jet-Powered Ponies\u2014NYC Maker Faire 2010 |author=Repanich, Jeremy |publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]] |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/home/how-to-plans/madagascar-institute-pulse-jet-powered-ponies-maker-faire-nyc-2010 |date=September 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n<!-- all episode descriptions were copy/pasted from http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/episodes.html, and are prohibited as copyvio.  Replaced those descriptions. -->\nEpisodes broadcast in 2011.<ref>[http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/episodes.html \"Episode Guide : Stuck with Hackett : Science Channel\"]. Science.Discovery.com.</ref>\n;Leaving on a Jet Train - August 18\nHackett starts with an abandoned rail yard, and fabricates a locomotive of sorts.\n\n;Laundromat of the Gods - August 25\nTo clean his junkyard-contaminated clothes, Hackett resurrects a washer and dryer from parts and an automobile, building a welder in the process\n\n;Hospital of Horror - September 1\nIn an abandoned medical facility, Hackett fabricates several types of hazardous artificial illumination.\n\n;The Suburbs Are for Suckers - September 8\nHackett constructs several types of power sources, in order to run modern electric conveniences in an abandoned desert home [[Off-the-grid|off the grid]].\n\n;Dirt Boat - September 22\nHackett builds a vehicle from parts at an abandoned aviation junkyard.\n\n;Really Freaking Fast Food - September 22\nTo prepare meals from food found in dumpsters, Hackett creates a kitchen in a machine shop.\n\n;Do Bears...? - September 29\nHackett builds a shower, a pump, and a water heater from found items in an abandoned RV camp.\n\n;Hackestivus! - October 6\nHackett invents a holiday at an abandoned munitions factory with devices, rockets and fireworks to celebrate.\n\n;Hot Tub on Ice - October 13\nHackett attempts to devise a hot tub built with snow, powered by the sun.\n\n== Reception ==\n''[[New York Times]]'' reviewer Neil Genzlinger wrote that Hackett's \"can-do spirit is admirable. This is the guy I want to be lost with when the [apocalypse] comes...\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Weathering Survivalist TV, Like \u2018Man vs. Wild\u2019\n | first=Neil |last=Genzlinger\n | date= December 29, 2010\n | work=[[New York Times]]\n | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/30/arts/television/30survival.html\n}}</ref>  In ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', Dave Giancaspro recommended the series to viewers.<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Stuck With Hackett Premieres 10 P.M. Tonight On The Science Channel\n | first=Dave |last=Giancaspro\n | date= December 10, 2010\n | work=Wired.com\n | url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/tag/stuck-with-hackett/\n}}</ref>  [[Common Sense Media]] used \"cool\", \"exceptional\", \"clear\" and \"compelling\" to describe the science lessons embodied in the show, while cautioning that kids should be taught not to follow Hackett's example of tearing apart his environment, and occasionally blowing things up; the non-profit group rated the show as appropriate for ages 9 and up.<ref>{{cite web\n | first=Matt |last=Springer\n | title=''Stuck With Hackett'' (Science)\n | url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/stuck-hackett\n | publisher=[[Common Sense Media]]\n | date=December 10, 2010\n | accessdate=October 16, 2011\n }}</ref>  In ''[[Media Life Magazine]]'', Tom Conroy found the show \"fun, engrossing and informative\", except for Hackett's overuse of the word \"obtainium.\"<ref name=\"MLM\"/> Of the pilot episode, Conroy wondered if an abandoned rail yard would have a working [[pump car]], a working gasoline engine, and nearby fueled-up lawn mowers, and wondered how much \"support\" Hackett received during the project. He found what Hackett achieved to be \"amazing\" nonetheless, and beyond the show's educational content, declared Hackett \"fun\".<ref name=\"MLM\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/ Stuck with Hackett Official Site]\n*[http://www.silvermachine.tv/ Silver Machine Company Site]\n*[http://www.madagascarinstitute.com Madagascar Institute Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Science Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series endings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Television series}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2011}}<!-- addressed advert issues -->\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Stuck with Hackett\n| image              = Hackett setting up engine.jpg\n| genre              = [[Documentary]]<br/>[[Science]]\n| creator            = [[Nathaniel Grouille]] <br/> [[Korelan Cone]]\n| starring           = Chris Hackett\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 1\n| num_episodes       = 9\n| runtime            = 30 minutes\n| distributor        = [[Science Channel]]\n| network            = [[Science Channel]]\n| first_run          = United States\n| first_aired        = {{start date|2011|8|18}}\n}}\n'''''Stuck with Hackett''''' is a television show created and produced by [[Silver Machine]] for the [[Science Channel]] .  It was commissioned as a pilot in 2010 and picked up as a nine-part series which began airing on August 18, 2011.  It follows the trials and tribulations of artist [[Chris Hackett (artist)|Chris Hackett]], founder of the [[Madagascar Institute]] as he turns everyday trash, into new and unexpected machines or mechanisms.\n\n== Format ==\nEach episode takes Hackett to a different abandoned location. In season one, Hackett visits a variety of places, including a rail yard, a munitions factory, and a log cabin.  After deciding what he\u2019s going to create to make his stay in the abandoned location more enjoyable, Hackett begins to collect various pieces of \"obtainium\",<ref name=\"MLM\">{{cite web\n |title='Stuck With Hackett,' and such a find\n |first=Tom \n |last=Conroy\n |date=August 18-October 13, 2011\n |work=[[Media Life Magazine]]\n |url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reviews_21/-Stuck-With-Hackett-and-such-a-find.asp\n}}</ref> a term he uses for anything from trash to scrap metal to large pieces of machinery that are being repurposed. Hackett then proceeds to construct the desired completed object, with \"off camera support\" of his production team.<ref name=\"MLM\"/>\n\n== Chris Hackett ==\n[[Chris Hackett (artist)|Chris Hackett]] is an artist who grew up in New York. He creates large, interactive art installations. He is the founder of The Madagascar Institute, an artist cooperative space based in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{cite web | title=Up Close With the Madagascar Institute's Pulse-Jet-Powered Ponies\u2014NYC Maker Faire 2010 |author=Repanich, Jeremy |publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]] |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/home/how-to-plans/madagascar-institute-pulse-jet-powered-ponies-maker-faire-nyc-2010 |date=September 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n<!-- all episode descriptions were copy/pasted from http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/episodes.html, and are prohibited as copyvio.  Replaced those descriptions. -->\nEpisodes broadcast in 2011.<ref>[http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/episodes.html \"Episode Guide : Stuck with Hackett : Science Channel\"]. Science.Discovery.com.</ref>\n;Leaving on a Jet Train - August 18\nHackett starts with an abandoned rail yard, and fabricates a locomotive of sorts.\n\n;Laundromat of the Gods - August 25\nTo clean his junkyard-contaminated clothes, Hackett resurrects a washer and dryer from parts and an automobile, building a welder in the process\n\n;Hospital of Horror - September 1\nIn an abandoned medical facility, Hackett fabricates several types of hazardous artificial illumination.\n\n;The Suburbs Are for Suckers - September 8\nHackett constructs several types of power sources, in order to run modern electric conveniences in an abandoned desert home [[Off-the-grid|off the grid]].\n\n;Dirt Boat - September 22\nHackett builds a vehicle from parts at an abandoned aviation junkyard.\n\n;Really Freaking Fast Food - September 22\nTo prepare meals from food found in dumpsters, Hackett creates a kitchen in a machine shop.\n\n;Do Bears...? - September 29\nHackett builds a shower, a pump, and a water heater from found items in an abandoned RV camp.\n\n;Hackestivus! - October 6\nHackett invents a holiday at an abandoned munitions factory with devices, rockets and fireworks to celebrate.\n\n;Hot Tub on Ice - October 13\nHackett attempts to devise a hot tub built with snow, powered by the sun.\n\n== Reception ==\n''[[New York Times]]'' reviewer Neil Genzlinger wrote that Hackett's \"can-do spirit is admirable. This is the guy I want to be lost with when the [apocalypse] comes...\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Weathering Survivalist TV, Like \u2018Man vs. Wild\u2019\n | first=Neil |last=Genzlinger\n | date= December 29, 2010\n | work=[[New York Times]]\n | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/30/arts/television/30survival.html\n}}</ref>  In ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', Dave Giancaspro recommended the series to viewers.<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Stuck With Hackett Premieres 10 P.M. Tonight On The Science Channel\n | first=Dave |last=Giancaspro\n | date= December 10, 2010\n | work=Wired.com\n | url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/tag/stuck-with-hackett/\n}}</ref>  [[Common Sense Media]] used \"cool\", \"exceptional\", \"clear\" and \"compelling\" to describe the science lessons embodied in the show, while cautioning that kids should be taught not to follow Hackett's example of tearing apart his environment, and occasionally blowing things up; the non-profit group rated the show as appropriate for ages 9 and up.<ref>{{cite web\n | first=Matt |last=Springer\n | title=''Stuck With Hackett'' (Science)\n | url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/stuck-hackett\n | publisher=[[Common Sense Media]]\n | date=December 10, 2010\n | accessdate=October 16, 2011\n }}</ref>  In ''[[Media Life Magazine]]'', Tom Conroy found the show \"fun, engrossing and informative\", except for Hackett's overuse of the word \"obtainium.\"<ref name=\"MLM\"/> Of the pilot episode, Conroy wondered if an abandoned rail yard would have a working [[pump car]], a working gasoline engine, and nearby fueled-up lawn mowers, and wondered how much \"support\" Hackett received during the project. He found what Hackett achieved to be \"amazing\" nonetheless, and beyond the show's educational content, declared Hackett \"fun\".<ref name=\"MLM\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://science.discovery.com/tv/stuck-with-hackett/ Stuck with Hackett Official Site]\n*[http://www.silvermachine.tv/ Silver Machine Company Site]\n*[http://www.madagascarinstitute.com Madagascar Institute Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Science Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series endings]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix cite date error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuck_with_Hackett"}
{"title_page": "Exeter Book Riddle 65", "text_new": "'''Exeter Book Riddle 25''' (according to the numbering of the [[Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records]])<ref name=\":0\">George Philip Krapp and Elliott Van Kirk Dobbie (eds), ''The Exeter Book'', The Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records, 3 (New York: Columbia University Press, 1936), http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206091232/http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009|date=2018-12-06}}.</ref> is one of the [[Old English]] [[Anglo-Saxon riddles|riddles]] found in the later tenth-century [[Exeter Book]]. Suggested solutions have included Onion, Leek, and Chives, but the consensus is that the solution is Onion.<ref name=\":1\">Judy Kendall, '[https://theriddleages.wordpress.com/2014/07/03/commentary-for-riddle-65/ Commentary for Riddle 65]', ''The Riddle Ages'' (17 August 2017).</ref>\n\n== Text and translation ==\nAs edited by Krapp and Dobbie and translated by Andrew Higl, the riddle reads:<ref>Andrew Higl, '[https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1153368.pdf Riddle Hero: Play and Poetry in the Exeter Book Riddles]', ''American Journal of Play'', 9 (2017), 374-94 (p. 389).</ref><ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|230}}\n{{Verse translation|{{lang|ang|\nCwico w\u00e6s ic, ne cw\u00e6\u00f0 ic wiht,  cwele ic efne se\u00feeah.\n\u00e6r ic w\u00e6s, eft ic cwom.  \u00e6ghwa mec reafa\u00f0,\nhafa\u00f0 mec on headre,  ond min heafod scire\u00fe,\nbite\u00f0 mec on b\u00e6r lic,  brice\u00f0 mine wisan.\nMonnan ic ne bite,  nymp\u00fee he me bite;\nsindan \u00feara monige  \u00fee mec bita\u00f0.}}|I was alive but did not speak;    even so I die.\nBack I came before I was.    Everyone plunders me,\nkeeps me confined,    and shears my head,\nbites on my bare body,    breaks my sprouts.\nI bite no one    unless the person bites me;\nmany there are    who do bite me.}}\n\n== Analogues ==\nThe riddle is frequently compared with [[Exeter Book Riddle 25]], also on the onion, but noted for its ''double entendre'', since in that riddle what to many readers will come first to mind as the obvious solution to the riddle is 'penis'.<ref name=\":1\" /> Meanwhile, its analogue in the late-antique Latin riddles of [[Symphosius]] is:<ref>Symphosius, ''The 'Aenigmata': An Introduction, Text, and Commentary'', ed. and trans. by T. J. Leary (London: Bloomsbury, 2014), p. 142 (no. 44).</ref>\n{{Verse translation|{{lang|lat|\nmordeo mordentes, ultro non mordeo quemquam;\nsed sunt mordentem multi mordere parati:\nnemo timet morsum, dentes quia non habet ullos.}}|\nI bite those who are biting; of my own accord I do not bite anyone;\nbut there are many ready to bite me as I am biting;\nno one fears my bite, since it does not have any teeth.}}\n\n== Editions ==\n\n* Krapp, George Philip and Elliott Van Kirk Dobbie (eds), ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20181206091232/http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009 The Exeter Book]'', The Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records, 3 (New York: Columbia University Press, 1936), p.&nbsp;230.\n* Williamson, Craig (ed.), ''The Old English Riddles of the Exeter Book'' (Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 1977).\n* Muir, Bernard J. (ed.), ''The Exeter Anthology of Old English Poetry: An Edition of Exeter Dean and Chapter MS 3501'', 2nd edn, 2 vols (Exeter: Exeter University Press, 2000).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "'''Exeter Book Riddle 25''' (according to the numbering of the [[Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records]])<ref name=\":0\">George Philip Krapp and Elliott Van Kirk Dobbie (eds), ''The Exeter Book'', The Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records, 3 (New York: Columbia University Press, 1936), http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206091232/http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009|date=2018-12-06}}.</ref> is one of the [[Old English]] [[Anglo-Saxon riddles|riddles]] found in the later tenth-century [[Exeter Book]]. Suggested solutions have included Onion, Leek, and Chives, but the consensus is that the solution is Onion.<ref name=\":1\">Judy Kendall, '[https://theriddleages.wordpress.com/2014/07/03/commentary-for-riddle-65/ Commentary for Riddle 65]', ''The Riddle Ages'' (17 August 2017).</ref>\n\n== Text and translation ==\nAs edited by Krapp and Dobbie and translated by Andrew Higl, the riddle reads:<ref>Andrew Higl, '[https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1153368.pdf Riddle Hero: Play and Poetry in the Exeter Book Riddles]', ''American Journal of Play'', 9 (2017), 374-94 (p. 389).</ref><ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|230}}\n{{Verse translation|{{lang|ang|\nCwico w\u00e6s ic, ne cw\u00e6\u00f0 ic wiht,  cwele ic efne se\u00feeah.\n\u00e6r ic w\u00e6s, eft ic cwom.  \u00e6ghwa mec reafa\u00f0,\nhafa\u00f0 mec on headre,  ond min heafod scire\u00fe,\nbite\u00f0 mec on b\u00e6r lic,  brice\u00f0 mine wisan.\nMonnan ic ne bite,  nymp\u00fee he me bite;\nsindan \u00feara monige  \u00fee mec bita\u00f0.}}|I was alive but did not speak;    even so I die.\nBack I came before I was.    Everyone plunders me,\nkeeps me confined,    and shears my head,\nbites on my bare body,    breaks my sprouts.\nI bite no one    unless the person bites me;\nmany there are    who do bite me.}}\n\n== Analogues ==\nThe riddle is frequently compared with [[Exeter Book Riddle 25]], also on the onion, but noted for its ''double entendre'', since in that riddle what to many readers will come first to mind as the obvious solution to the riddle is 'penis'.<ref name=\":1\" /> Meanwhile, its analogue in the late-antique Latin riddles of [[Symphosius]] is:<ref>Symphosius, <i>The 'Aenigmata': An Introduction, Text, and Commentary</i>, ed. and trans. by T. J. Leary (London: Bloomsbury, 2014), p. 142 (no. 44).</ref>\n{{Verse translation|{{lang|lat|\nmordeo mordentes, ultro non mordeo quemquam;\nsed sunt mordentem multi mordere parati:\nnemo timet morsum, dentes quia non habet ullos.}}|\nI bite those who are biting; of my own accord I do not bite anyone;\nbut there are many ready to bite me as I am biting;\nno one fears my bite, since it does not have any teeth.}}\n\n== Editions ==\n\n* Krapp, George Philip and Elliott Van Kirk Dobbie (eds), ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20181206091232/http://ota.ox.ac.uk/desc/3009 The Exeter Book]'', The Anglo-Saxon Poetic Records, 3 (New York: Columbia University Press, 1936), p. 230.\n* Williamson, Craig (ed.), ''The Old English Riddles of the Exeter Book'' (Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 1977).\n* Muir, Bernard J. (ed.), ''The Exeter Anthology of Old English Poetry: An Edition of Exeter Dean and Chapter MS 3501'', 2nd edn, 2 vols (Exeter: Exeter University Press, 2000).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exeter_Book_Riddle_65"}
{"title_page": "The Face of Mercy", "text_new": "{{short description|Documentary about St. Faustina}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Face of Mercy\n| image          = The Face of Mercy poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = David Naglieri\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Knights of Columbus]]\n* [[Congregation of the Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = David Naglieri\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jim Caviezel]]\n* [[Scott Hahn]]\n* [[George Weigel]]\n* Fr. Michael Gaitley\n}}\n| music          = Sean Beeson\n| cinematography = George Hosek\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Marc Boudignon\n* Ted Maynard\n}}\n| studio         = Spirit Juice Studios\n| distributor    = [[American Broadcasting Company]]<ref>{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy: Documentary Features Stories of Divine Mercy to Transform the World |url=https://stream.org/the-face-of-mercy-documentary-features-stories-of-divine-mercy-to-transform-the-world/}}</ref>\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|10|16}}\n| runtime        = 57 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''The Face of Mercy''''' is a 2016 documentary about [[St. Faustina]], her mystical visions, and the role mercy, namely Christ-like mercy, [[Divine Mercy]], has played in different people's lives. It is narrated by [[Jim Caviezel]],<ref>{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy DVD \u2013 Narrated by Jim Caviezel |url=https://divinemercyforamerica.org/product/store/videos/the-face-of-mercy-dvd/}}</ref> but also includes testimonials from those whose lives have been changed by [[Jesus Christ]]'s mercy.\n\n[[Carl A. Anderson|Carl Anderson]], the Supreme Knight of [[The Knights of Columbus]], in a statement, said that \"this extraordinary film highlights the sort of transformations that are possible in individual lives that embrace the way of mercy, forgiveness and reconciliation.\" He continued saying, \"Throughout the twentieth century, the Catholic understanding of Divine Mercy became increasingly important. Both [[St. John Paul II]], and [[Pope Francis]], who declared this Year of Mercy, made it a central theme of their papacies.\"<ref>{{cite website |title=New film highlights the \u2018Face of Mercy\u2019 at year\u2019s close |url=https://cruxnow.com/church-in-the-usa/2016/11/new-film-highlights-face-mercy-years-close/}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn 2015, [[Pope Francis]] declared an [[Extraordinary Jubilee of Mercy]]. The \"year of mercy\"<ref>{{ cite news |title=Everything you need to know about the Holy Year of Mercy |url=https://cruxnow.com/church/2015/12/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-holy-year-of-mercy/}}</ref> began on December 8, 2015, the [[Feast of the Immaculate Conception]], and ended on 20 November 2016. {{quote|Since his election to the papacy, Pope Francis has inspired millions by urging us to embrace Mercy, ultimately revealed in the face of Christ. Now comes an extraordinary new film on this powerful message that brings hope, healing and forgiveness to a broken world.<ref name=FOMfilm >{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy |url=https://faceofmercyfilm.com/about/}}</ref>}} The documentary \"draws connections between the history of Divine Mercy and this year's Extraordinary Jubilee Year of Mercy\" and weaves together a thoughtful, beautiful, and educational film.<ref>{{cite website |title=Documentary on How God's Mercy Transforms Lives to Air on ABC Affiliates |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/documentary-on-how-gods-mercy-transforms-lives-to-air-on-abc-affiliates-300345129.html}}</ref> Thus it is fitting that it is Pope Francis who says the first lines on screen. This is the context for this documentary, which came out during the last month of the Extraordinary [[jubilee (Christianity)|Jubilee]].\n\nOne of the first things said in the documentary, during the opening montage, is that \"mercy is loves second name,\" which is a paraphrased quote of [[St. John Paul II]]. Divine Mercy, they argue, is God's response to the horrors of the [[20th Century]].<ref>{{cite website |title=\u2018The Face of Mercy\u2019 Film Offers Hope to a Hurting World |url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-face-of-mercy-film-offers-hope-to-a-hurting-world}}</ref> It is the antidote given to man from Jesus through St. Faustina for the benefit of all mankind. It proves this by weaving together a story consisting of Theology, History, and testimonials.\n\n===History===\nIt begins with the history of St. Faustina and how St. John Paul II (Karol Wojty\u0142a) brought the message given to St. Faustina by God. It also highlights the influence Divine Mercy played in the life in the young Wojty\u0142a. [[George Weigel]] explains that this devotion culminated years later in his second [[Encyclical]] entitled ''[[Dives in Misericordia]]'' (or ''Rich in Mercy'').<ref>{{cite website |title= Dives in Misericoria|url=http://www.vatican.va/content/john-paul-ii/en/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_30111980_dives-in-misericordia.html}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Weigel are John Allen, a Vatican Journalist, and [[Andrzej Duda]], the President of [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite website |title=The Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy_The Face of Mercy |url=https://www.sisterfaustina.com/faceofmercy.html?viewfullsite=1}}</ref> They both tell of their unique perspectives on Divine Mercy, putting it in even more significant historical context.\n\n===Theology===\nLead by [[Scott Hahn]], [[Marc Ouellet|Cardinal Marc Ouellet]], Fr. Michael Gaitley, [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Cardinal Se\u00e1n O'Malley]], and Fr. Seraphim Michalenko, the film uncovers the depth of the message St. Faustina received from Jesus. The \"Face of Mercy\" is the face of Jesus himself, because Jesus is [[Charity (virtue)|Love]] incarnate. Furthermore, Weigel articulates the message of John Paul II's ''Dives in Misericordia'' saying, \"In Christ we meet the Merciful face of the Father and the Truth about our Humanity.\"<ref>[https://watch.formed.org/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel/videos/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel \"''The Face of Mercy''\"] on ''Formed''</ref> Thus, Divine Mercy, the Face of Mercy, the face of Jesus, is the proper remedy for the atrocities of the 20th and 21st Centuries. This is clearly what John Paul the Great believed, for, when he became [[Pope]], he instituted [[Divine Mercy Sunday]]. Furthermore, the first saint he canonized in the [[21st Century]] was St. Faustina!<ref>{{cite website |title=St. Faustina in Film |url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/st.-faustina-in-film}}</ref>\n\n===Testimonials===\nThere are a plethora of testimonials in this documentary. \"These moving testimonies will remind us all that Divine Mercy is not just a devotion of the past or some abstract theology \u2013 it is alive, it is present, and it will transform the world.\"<ref name=FOMfilm /> They include, but aren't limited to those of:\n* Maureen Digan, who had [[Lymphedema]], which is a fatal cancer which causes swelling in the limbs. She was miraculously cured after praying to St. Faustina, the second miracle attributed to St. Faustina, which made her eligible for [[canonization]];<ref>{{cite website |title=The Miracle of Maureen Digan |url=https://www.divinemercy.org/elements-of-divine-mercy/miracles/166-the-miracle-of-maureen-dignan.html}}</ref> \n* [[Steven McDonald|Detective Steven McDonald]], a former [[NYPD]] [[police officer]] who forgave the criminal who shot and paralyzed him;\n* [[Immacul\u00e9e Ilibagiza]], a survivor of the [[Rwandan Genocide]], who hid with seven other [[Tutsi]] women in a small bathroom. She prayed the [[Divine Mercy Chaplet]] continuously (40 times each day) for weeks when the [[genocide]] was occurring. She was miraculously never found by [[Hutu]] soldiers. In her book, ''Left to Tell'', she describes how she realized that she too had to have mercy, especially on those who killed her family members;<ref>{{cite website |title=Left to Tell: Discovering God Amidst the Rwandan Holocaust |url=https://www.amazon.com/Left-Tell-Discovering-Rwandan-Holocaust/dp/1401908977}}</ref>\n* Eric Mahl, a former [[NFL]] [[linebacker]] who gave up his career to teach the homeless about Divine Mercy and the Love of Christ;\n* A [[Nun]] who was influenced by the letters of St. Faustina and Divine Mercy;\n* Fr. Donald Calloway, a [[Catholic Priest|priest]], who calls himself the \"Poster Child of Divine Mercy\"<ref>{{cite website |title=Poster Child for Divine Mercy \u2014 the inspirational testimony of Fr. Donald Calloway, MIC |url=https://www.catechist.com/poster-child-divine-mercy-inspirational-testimony-fr-donald-calloway-mic/}}</ref> because he was a drug dealer and a wanted criminal. In the documentary he explains his self-given nickname saying that if God could forgive ''him'' then He can forgive anyone, anyone who asks;\n* A [[widowed]] wife who forgave the person who murdered her husband; and\n* A professional [[baseball player]] who gave up his baseball career to give his life to God and became a priest.\n\n==Film Festivals Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title!! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|International Lisbon Film Festival<ref>{{cite website |title=Lisbon International Film Festival |url=https://www.facebook.com/lisbonfilmfestival/photos/a.509551719225054/671793239667567/?type=3&theater}}</ref>\n| Winter Edition\n|-\n|2017\n| International Christian Film Festival<ref>{{cite website |title=2017 Official Selection |url=https://www.internationalcff.org/2017-official-selection/}} on ''International Christian Film Festival''</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|6194886|The Face of Mercy}}\n*[https://watch.formed.org/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel/videos/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel  ''The Face of Mercy''] on Formed.org\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Documentary about St. Faustina}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Face of Mercy\n| image          = The Face of Mercy poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = David Naglieri\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Knights of Columbus]]\n* [[Congregation of the Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = David Naglieri\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jim Caviezel]]\n* [[Scott Hahn]]\n* [[George Weigel]]\n* Fr. Michael Gaitley\n}}\n| music          = Sean Beeson\n| cinematography = George Hosek\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Marc Boudignon\n* Ted Maynard\n}}\n| studio         = Spirit Juice Studios\n| distributor    = [[American Broadcasting Company]]<ref>{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy: Documentary Features Stories of Divine Mercy to Transform the World |url=https://stream.org/the-face-of-mercy-documentary-features-stories-of-divine-mercy-to-transform-the-world/}}</ref>\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|10|16}}\n| runtime        = 57 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''The Face of Mercy''''' is a 2016 documentary about [[St. Faustina]], her mystical visions, and the role mercy, namely Christ-like mercy, [[Divine Mercy]], has played in different people's lives. It is narrated by [[Jim Caviezel]],<ref>{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy DVD \u2013 Narrated by Jim Caviezel |url=https://divinemercyforamerica.org/product/store/videos/the-face-of-mercy-dvd/}}</ref> but also includes testimonials from those whose lives have been changed by [[Jesus Christ]]'s mercy.\n\n[[Carl A. Anderson |Carl Anderson]], the Supreme Knight of [[The Knights of Columbus]], in a statement, said that \"this extraordinary film highlights the sort of transformations that are possible in individual lives that embrace the way of mercy, forgiveness and reconciliation.\" He continued saying, \"Throughout the twentieth century, the Catholic understanding of Divine Mercy became increasingly important. Both [[St. John Paul II]], and [[Pope Francis]], who declared this Year of Mercy, made it a central theme of their papacies.\"<ref>{{cite website |title=New film highlights the \u2018Face of Mercy\u2019 at year\u2019s close |url=https://cruxnow.com/church-in-the-usa/2016/11/new-film-highlights-face-mercy-years-close/}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn 2015, [[Pope Francis]] declared an [[Extraordinary Jubilee of Mercy]]. The \"year of mercy\"<ref>{{ cite news |title=Everything you need to know about the Holy Year of Mercy |url=https://cruxnow.com/church/2015/12/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-holy-year-of-mercy/}}</ref> began on December 8, 2015, the [[Feast of the Immaculate Conception]], and ended on 20th of November 2016. {{quote|Since his election to the papacy, Pope Francis has inspired millions by urging us to embrace Mercy, ultimately revealed in the face of Christ. Now comes an extraordinary new film on this powerful message that brings hope, healing and forgiveness to a broken world.<ref name=FOMfilm >{{cite website |title=The Face of Mercy |url=https://faceofmercyfilm.com/about/}}</ref>}} The documentary \"draws connections between the history of Divine Mercy and this year's Extraordinary Jubilee Year of Mercy\" and weaves together a thoughtful, beautiful, and educational film.<ref>{{cite website |title=Documentary on How God's Mercy Transforms Lives to Air on ABC Affiliates |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/documentary-on-how-gods-mercy-transforms-lives-to-air-on-abc-affiliates-300345129.html}}</ref> Thus it is fitting that it is Pope Francis who says the first lines on screen. This is the context for this documentary, which came out during the last month of the Extraordinary [[jubilee (Christianity) |Jubilee]]. \n\nOne of the first things said in the documentary, during the opening montage, is that \"mercy is loves second name,\" which is a paraphrased quote of [[St. John Paul II]]. Divine Mercy, they argue, is God's response to the horrors of the [[20th Century]].<ref>{{cite website |title=\u2018The Face of Mercy\u2019 Film Offers Hope to a Hurting World |url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-face-of-mercy-film-offers-hope-to-a-hurting-world}}</ref> It is the antidote given to man from Jesus through St. Faustina for the benefit of all mankind. It proves this by weaving together a story consisting of Theology, History, and testimonials. \n\n===History===\nIt begins with the history of St. Faustina and how St. John Paul II (Karol Wojty\u0142a) brought the message given to St. Faustina by God. It also highlights the influence Divine Mercy played in the life in the young Wojty\u0142a. [[George Weigel]] explains that this devotion culminated years later in his second [[Encyclical]] entitled ''[[Dives in Misericordia]]'' (or ''Rich in Mercy'').<ref>{{cite website |title= Dives in Misericoria|url=http://www.vatican.va/content/john-paul-ii/en/encyclicals/documents/hf_jp-ii_enc_30111980_dives-in-misericordia.html}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Weigel are John Allen, a Vatican Journalist, and [[Andrzej Duda]], the President of [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite website |title=The Sisters of Our Lady of Mercy_The Face of Mercy |url=https://www.sisterfaustina.com/faceofmercy.html?viewfullsite=1}}</ref> They both tell of their unique perspectives on Divine Mercy, putting it in even more significant historical context.\n\n===Theology===\nLead by [[Scott Hahn]], [[Marc Ouellet |Cardinal Marc Ouellet]], Fr. Michael Gaitley, [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley |Cardinal Se\u00e1n O'Malley]], and Fr. Seraphim Michalenko, the film uncovers the depth of the message St. Faustina received from Jesus. The \"Face of Mercy\" is the face of Jesus himself, because Jesus is [[Charity (virtue) |Love]] incarnate. Furthermore, Weigel articulates the message of John Paul II's ''Dives in Misericordia'' saying, \"In Christ we meet the Merciful face of the Father and the Truth about our Humanity.\"<ref>[https://watch.formed.org/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel/videos/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel \"''The Face of Mercy''\"] on ''Formed''</ref> Thus, Divine Mercy, the Face of Mercy, the face of Jesus, is the proper remedy for the atrocities of the 20th and 21st Centuries. This is clearly what John Paul the Great believed, for, when he became [[Pope]], he instituted [[Divine Mercy Sunday]]. Furthermore, the first saint he canonized in the [[21st Century]] was St. Faustina!<ref>{{cite website |title=St. Faustina in Film |url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/st.-faustina-in-film}}</ref>\n\n===Testimonials===\nThere are a plethora of testimonials in this documentary. \"These moving testimonies will remind us all that Divine Mercy is not just a devotion of the past or some abstract theology \u2013 it is alive, it is present, and it will transform the world.\"<ref name=FOMfilm /> They include, but aren't limited to those of:\n* Maureen Digan, who had [[Lymphedema]], which is a fatal cancer which causes swelling in the limbs. She was miraculously cured after praying to St. Faustina, the second miracle attributed to to St. Faustina, which made her eligible for [[canonization]];<ref>{{cite website |title=The Miracle of Maureen Digan |url=https://www.divinemercy.org/elements-of-divine-mercy/miracles/166-the-miracle-of-maureen-dignan.html}}</ref> \n* [[Steven McDonald |Detective Steven McDonald]], a former [[NYPD]] [[police officer]] who forgave the criminal who shot and paralyzed him;\n* [[Immacul\u00e9e Ilibagiza]], a survivor of the [[Rwandan Genocide]], who hid with seven other [[Tutsi]] women in a small bathroom. She prayed the [[Divine Mercy Chaplet]] continuously (40 times each day) for weeks when the [[genocide]] was occurring. She was miraculously never found by [[Hutu]] soldiers. In her book, ''Left to Tell'', she describes how she realized that she too had to have mercy, especially on those who killed her family members;<ref>{{cite website |title=Left to Tell: Discovering God Amidst the Rwandan Holocaust |url=https://www.amazon.com/Left-Tell-Discovering-Rwandan-Holocaust/dp/1401908977}}</ref>\n* Eric Mahl, a former [[NFL]] [[linebacker]] who gave up his career to teach the homeless about Divine Mercy and the Love of Christ;\n* A [[Nun]] who was influenced by the letters of St. Faustina and Divine Mercy;\n* Fr. Donald Calloway, a [[Catholic Priest |priest]], who calls himself the \"Poster Child of Divine Mercy\"<ref>{{cite website |title=Poster Child for Divine Mercy \u2014 the inspirational testimony of Fr. Donald Calloway, MIC |url=https://www.catechist.com/poster-child-divine-mercy-inspirational-testimony-fr-donald-calloway-mic/}}</ref> because he was a drug dealer and a wanted criminal. In the documentary he explains his self-given nickname saying that if God could forgive ''him'' then He can forgive anyone, anyone who asks;\n* A [[widowed]] wife who forgave the person who murdered her husband; and\n* A professional [[baseball player]] who gave up his baseball career to give his life to God and became a priest.\n\n==Film Festivals Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title!! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|International Lisbon Film Festival<ref>{{cite website |title=Lisbon International Film Festival |url=https://www.facebook.com/lisbonfilmfestival/photos/a.509551719225054/671793239667567/?type=3&theater}}</ref>\n| Winter Edition\n|-\n|2017\n| International Christian Film Festival<ref>{{cite website |title=2017 Official Selection |url=https://www.internationalcff.org/2017-official-selection/}} on ''International Christian Film Festival''</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*{{IMDb title|6194886|The Face of Mercy}}\n*[https://watch.formed.org/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel/videos/the-face-of-mercy-narrated-by-jim-caviezel| ''The Face of Mercy''] on Formed.org\n\n\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: to to \u2192 to", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Face_of_Mercy"}
{"title_page": "Paolo Fresu", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name            = Paolo Fresu\n|image           = Paolo Fresu Ibk.JPG\n|caption         =  Paolo Fresu \n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_date      =  {{birth date and age|1961|2|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Berchidda]], Sardinia\n|genre =  [[Jazz]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place     =\n|occupation = Musician, composer, arranger, producer\n|instrument = Trumpet, [[flugelhorn]] \n|label = [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n|website = {{URL|www.paolofresu.it}}\n}}\n\n'''Paolo Fresu''' (born 10 February 1961) is an Italian [[jazz]] trumpet and [[flugelhorn]] player, as well as a composer and arranger of music.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Berchidda]], [[Sardinia]], he picked up the [[trumpet]] at the age of 11, and played in the band [[Bernardo de Muro]] in his home town Berchidda.<ref>[http://www.paolofresu.it/site/index.htm Official biography]</ref> Fresu graduated from the [[Conservatory (school)|Conservatory]] of [[Cagliari]] in 1984, in trumpet studies under Enzo Morandini, and attended the [[University of Bologna]] School of music and [[performing arts]] in [[Bologna]].<ref>Jazz Musiques Productions [https://www.jmp.fr/artistes/item/root/paolo-fresu.html Paolo Fresu] Retrieved August 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nHe has taught at the [[Siena, Italy|Siena]] Jazz National [[Seminar]]s, as well as jazz university courses in [[Terni]], and is the director of Nuoro Jazz Seminars in [[Nuoro]], Italy.<ref>Tommaso Starace [http://www.tommasostarace.com/media/cms_page_media/2/long_cv_Li8FeJr.pdf Tommaso Starace Biography] Retrieved August 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nFresu composes music for theatre, poem, dance, radio, television, and film.\n\nIn 2007, he recorded and toured with [[Carla Bley]]'s quartet, the Lost Chords.\n\nIn 2011, he released ''Mistico Mediterraneo'', which featured him, Daniele di Bonaventura and five other members playing [[bandoneon]]s in [[A Filetta]] style.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2011-02-23/trumpet-virtuoso-paolo-fresu|author=Ken Bader|title=Trumpet virtuoso Paolo Fresu|publisher=[[Public Radio International]]|date=February 23, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, his quintet performed at the [[Sirifort Auditorium]], New Delhi, [[India]], to celebrate 10 years of the Italian culture center there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delhiites have a date with Italian jazz quintet|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-14/delhi/31700924_1_italian-jazz-italian-art-concert|accessdate=May 14, 2012|work=The Times of India|date=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Fresu was awarded an honorary doctorate of music from Berklee College of Music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/massachusetts/backbay/berklee-presents-umbria-jazz-founder-carlo-pagnotta-george-wein-impresario-award-honorary-doctorates|title=Berklee Presents Umbria Jazz Founder Carlo Pagnotta with George Wein Impresario Award and Honorary Doctorates to Paolo Fresu and Charles Lloyd|date=2015-07-13|website=Back Bay, MA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Carla-Bley-crop.png|thumb|240px|right|''The Lost Chords find Paolo Fresu'' in [[Monaco]]. From left to right: [[Carla Bley]], Paolo Fresu and [[Andy Sheppard]]]]\n\n* 1987 ''Mamut: Music for a Mime'' (Splasc(H), 1987)\n* 1989 ''Opale'' with Francesco Tattara, Furio Di Castri (Clac, 1989)\n* 1991 ''Umiliani Jazz Family'' with [[Piero Umiliani]] (Liuto Edizioni Musicali, 1991)\n* 1993 ''Contos'' with Furio Di Castri, [[John Taylor (jazz)|John Taylor]] (EGEA, 1993)\n* 1995 ''Palatino'' with [[Aldo Romano]], [[Michel Benita]], [[Glenn Ferris]] ([[Label Bleu]], 1995)\n* 1995 ''Mythscapes'' with Furio Di Castri, [[Jon Balke]], [[Pierre Favre (musician)|Pierre Favre]] ([[Soul Note Records|Soul Note]], 1995)\n* 1996 ''The Hands'' with Flavio Piras, Furio Di Castri, Antonello Salis (Amiata, 1996)\n* 1997 ''Wanderlust'' ([[RCA Victor]], 1997)\n* 1998 ''Palatino Tempo'' with Aldo Romano, Michel Benita, Glenn Ferris (Label Bleu, 1998)\n* 1998 ''Condaghes'' with Jacques Pellen, [[Erik Marchand]] (Silex)\n* 1998 ''Things Left Behind'' with Iridescente Ensemble (Symphonia)\n* 1999 ''Metamorfosi'' (RCA Victor)\n* 1999 ''Shades of Chet'' with [[Enrico Rava]] (Via Veneto Jazz)\n* 2001 ''Porgy and Bess'' with Orchestra Jazz Della Sardegna (Il Manifesto)\n* 2001 ''Heartland'' with [[David Linx]], [[Diederik Wissels]]  ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]])\n* 2002 ''Kind of Porgy & Bess'' (RCA Victor)\n* 2003 ''Scores'' ([[CAM Jazz]])\n* 2006 ''Homescape'' with [[Nguyen Le]], [[Dhafer Youssef]] ([[ACT Music|ACT]])\n* 2007 ''Mare Nostrum'' with [[Richard Galliano]], [[Jan Lundgren]] (ACT)\n* 2008 ''Le Fresiadi'' (Time in Jazz)\n* 2009 ''Jazzitaliano Live 2009'' (Casa del Jazz)\n* 2011 ''Alma'' with [[Omar Sosa]] (Tuk)\n* 2012 ''Birth of the Cool'' (Musica Jazz)\n* 2013 ''Vinodentro'' (Tuk)\n* 2014 ''Brass Bang!'' with [[Steven Bernstein (musician)|Steven Bernstein]], [[Gianluca Petrella]], [[Marcus Rojas]] (Tuk)\n* 2015 ''The Whistleblowers'' with David Linx, Diederik Wissels (Tuk)\n* 2016 ''Mare Nostrum II'' with Richard Galliano, Jan Lundgren (ACT)\n* 2016 ''Eros'' with Omar Sosa, [[Jaques Morelenbaum]], [[Natacha Atlas]] (Tuk)\n* 2016 ''Around Tuk'' (Casa del Jazz)\n* 2017 ''Danse Memoire, Danse'' (Tuk)\n* 2019 ''Mare Nostrum'' with Richard Galliano, Jan Lundgren (ACT)\n\n===As sideman===\n\n'''With [[Joe Barbieri]]'''\n* ''Origami'', (Microcosmo Dischi, 2017)\n\n'''With [[Carla Bley]]'''\n* ''[[The Lost Chords find Paolo Fresu]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]]/Watt, 2007)\n\n'''With Daniele di Bonaventura'''\n* ''Mistico Mediterraneo'', ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 2011)\n* ''[[In maggiore]]'', ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 2015)\n\n'''With [[Uri Caine]]'''\n* ''[[Things (album)|Things]]'' (Blue Note, 2006)\n* ''Two Minuettos'' (T\u01d4k Music, 2016)\n\n'''With [[Lars Danielsson]]'''\n* ''Summerwind'' (ACT, 2018)\n\n'''With [[Aldo Romano]]'''\n* ''Ritual'' (Owl, 1988)\n\n'''With [[Ralph Towner]]'''\n* ''[[Chiaroscuro (Ralph Towner album)|Chiaroscuro]]'' (ECM, 2008)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jazz arrangers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.paolofresu.it/ Paolo Fresu's official site]\n\n{{Nastro d'Argento Best Score}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fresu, Paolo}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Sassari]]\n[[Category:Flugelhorn players]]\n[[Category:Italian jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Male trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Italian composers]]\n[[Category:Music in Sardinia]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n[[Category:Nastro d'Argento winners]]\n[[Category:Italian jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name            = Paolo Fresu\n|image           = Paolo Fresu Ibk.JPG\n|caption         =  Paolo Fresu \n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_date      =  {{birth date and age|1961|2|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Berchidda]], Sardinia\n|genre =  [[Jazz]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place     =\n|occupation = Musician, composer, arranger, producer\n|instrument = Trumpet, [[flugelhorn]] \n|label = [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n|website = {{URL|www.paolofresu.it}}\n}}\n\n'''Paolo Fresu''' (born 10 February 1961) is an Italian [[jazz]] trumpet and [[flugelhorn]] player, as well as a composer and arranger of music.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Berchidda]], [[Sardinia]], he picked up the [[trumpet]] at the age of 11, and played in the band [[Bernardo de Muro]] in his home town Berchidda.<ref>[http://www.paolofresu.it/site/index.htm Official biography]</ref> Fresu graduated from the [[Conservatory (school)|Conservatory]] of [[Cagliari]] in 1984, in trumpet studies under Enzo Morandini, and attended the [[University of Bologna]] School of music and [[performing arts]] in [[Bologna]].<ref>Jazz Musiques Productions [https://www.jmp.fr/artistes/item/root/paolo-fresu.html Paolo Fresu] Retrieved August 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nHe has taught at the [[Siena, Italy|Siena]] Jazz National [[Seminar]]s, as well as jazz university courses in [[Terni]], and is the director of Nuoro Jazz Seminars in [[Nuoro]], Italy.<ref>Tommaso Starace [http://www.tommasostarace.com/media/cms_page_media/2/long_cv_Li8FeJr.pdf Tommaso Starace Biography] Retrieved August 29, 2019.</ref>\n\nFresu composes music for theatre, poem, dance, radio, television, and film.\n\nIn 2007, he recorded and toured with [[Carla Bley]]'s quartet, the Lost Chords.\n\nIn 2011, he released ''Mistico Mediterraneo'', which featured him, Daniele di Bonaventura and five other members playing [[bandoneon]]s in [[A Filetta]] style.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2011-02-23/trumpet-virtuoso-paolo-fresu|author=Ken Bader|title=Trumpet virtuoso Paolo Fresu|publisher=[[Public Radio International]]|date=February 23, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, his quintet performed at the [[Sirifort Auditorium]], New Delhi, [[India]], to celebrate 10 years of the Italian culture center there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delhiites have a date with Italian jazz quintet|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-14/delhi/31700924_1_italian-jazz-italian-art-concert|accessdate=May 14, 2012|work=The Times of India|date=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Carla-Bley-crop.png|thumb|240px|right|''The Lost Chords find Paolo Fresu'' in [[Monaco]]. From left to right: [[Carla Bley]], Paolo Fresu and [[Andy Sheppard]]]]\n\n* 1987 ''Mamut: Music for a Mime'' (Splasc(H), 1987)\n* 1989 ''Opale'' with Francesco Tattara, Furio Di Castri (Clac, 1989)\n* 1991 ''Umiliani Jazz Family'' with [[Piero Umiliani]] (Liuto Edizioni Musicali, 1991)\n* 1993 ''Contos'' with Furio Di Castri, [[John Taylor (jazz)|John Taylor]] (EGEA, 1993)\n* 1995 ''Palatino'' with [[Aldo Romano]], [[Michel Benita]], [[Glenn Ferris]] ([[Label Bleu]], 1995)\n* 1995 ''Mythscapes'' with Furio Di Castri, [[Jon Balke]], [[Pierre Favre (musician)|Pierre Favre]] ([[Soul Note Records|Soul Note]], 1995)\n* 1996 ''The Hands'' with Flavio Piras, Furio Di Castri, Antonello Salis (Amiata, 1996)\n* 1997 ''Wanderlust'' ([[RCA Victor]], 1997)\n* 1998 ''Palatino Tempo'' with Aldo Romano, Michel Benita, Glenn Ferris (Label Bleu, 1998)\n* 1998 ''Condaghes'' with Jacques Pellen, [[Erik Marchand]] (Silex)\n* 1998 ''Things Left Behind'' with Iridescente Ensemble (Symphonia)\n* 1999 ''Metamorfosi'' (RCA Victor)\n* 1999 ''Shades of Chet'' with [[Enrico Rava]] (Via Veneto Jazz)\n* 2001 ''Porgy and Bess'' with Orchestra Jazz Della Sardegna (Il Manifesto)\n* 2001 ''Heartland'' with [[David Linx]], [[Diederik Wissels]]  ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]])\n* 2002 ''Kind of Porgy & Bess'' (RCA Victor)\n* 2003 ''Scores'' ([[CAM Jazz]])\n* 2006 ''Homescape'' with [[Nguyen Le]], [[Dhafer Youssef]] ([[ACT Music|ACT]])\n* 2007 ''Mare Nostrum'' with [[Richard Galliano]], [[Jan Lundgren]] (ACT)\n* 2008 ''Le Fresiadi'' (Time in Jazz)\n* 2009 ''Jazzitaliano Live 2009'' (Casa del Jazz)\n* 2011 ''Alma'' with [[Omar Sosa]] (Tuk)\n* 2012 ''Birth of the Cool'' (Musica Jazz)\n* 2013 ''Vinodentro'' (Tuk)\n* 2014 ''Brass Bang!'' with [[Steven Bernstein (musician)|Steven Bernstein]], [[Gianluca Petrella]], [[Marcus Rojas]] (Tuk)\n* 2015 ''The Whistleblowers'' with David Linx, Diederik Wissels (Tuk)\n* 2016 ''Mare Nostrum II'' with Richard Galliano, Jan Lundgren (ACT)\n* 2016 ''Eros'' with Omar Sosa, [[Jaques Morelenbaum]], [[Natacha Atlas]] (Tuk)\n* 2016 ''Around Tuk'' (Casa del Jazz)\n* 2017 ''Danse Memoire, Danse'' (Tuk)\n* 2019 ''Mare Nostrum'' with Richard Galliano, Jan Lundgren (ACT)\n\n===As sideman===\n\n'''With [[Joe Barbieri]]'''\n* ''Origami'', (Microcosmo Dischi, 2017)\n\n'''With [[Carla Bley]]'''\n* ''[[The Lost Chords find Paolo Fresu]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]]/Watt, 2007)\n\n'''With Daniele di Bonaventura'''\n* ''Mistico Mediterraneo'', ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 2011)\n* ''[[In maggiore]]'', ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 2015)\n\n'''With [[Uri Caine]]'''\n* ''[[Things (album)|Things]]'' (Blue Note, 2006)\n* ''Two Minuettos'' (T\u01d4k Music, 2016)\n\n'''With [[Lars Danielsson]]'''\n* ''Summerwind'' (ACT, 2018)\n\n'''With [[Aldo Romano]]'''\n* ''Ritual'' (Owl, 1988)\n\n'''With [[Ralph Towner]]'''\n* ''[[Chiaroscuro (Ralph Towner album)|Chiaroscuro]]'' (ECM, 2008)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jazz arrangers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.paolofresu.it/ Paolo Fresu's official site]\n\n{{Nastro d'Argento Best Score}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fresu, Paolo}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Sassari]]\n[[Category:Flugelhorn players]]\n[[Category:Italian jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Male trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Italian composers]]\n[[Category:Music in Sardinia]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n[[Category:Nastro d'Argento winners]]\n[[Category:Italian jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]