{"title_page": "Pieter Groenewald", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n | name               = Pieter Groenewald\n | native_name        = \n | native_name_lang   = \n | honorific_suffix   = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]] \n | image              = [[File:PJ Groenewald.jpg|220px]]\n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      =\n | smallimage         = \n | alt                = \n | caption            = Groenewald in 2018\n | order              = \n | office             = Leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus]]\n | term_start         =  12 November 2016\n | term_end           = \n | alongside          = \n | monarch            = \n | president          = \n | governor_general   = \n | primeminister      = \n | taoiseach          = \n | chancellor         = \n | governor           = \n | chair              = \n | vicepresident      = \n | viceprimeminister  = \n | deputy             = \n | lieutenant         = \n | vicechair          = \n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup = \n | constituency       = \n | majority           = \n | predecessor        = [[Pieter Mulder]]\n | successor          = \n | prior_term         =\n | order2             =  \n | office2            =  Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]]\n | term_start2        =  2001\n | term_end2          =  \n | predecessor2       =  \n | successor2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | parliamentarygroup2=  \n | constituency2      =  \n | majority2          =  \n | prior_term2        =  \n | office3            =  \n | term_start3        =   9 May 1994\n | term_end3          =  1 June 1999\n | predecessor3       =  \n | successor3         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | parliamentarygroup3=  \n | constituency3      =  \n | majority3          =  \n | prior_term3        =  \n | office4            = Federal Chairperson of the [[Freedom Front Plus]] \n | term_start4        = 11 August 2011\n | term_end4          = 12 November 2016\n | predecessor4       = [[Abrie Oosthuizen]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/mulder-earns-another-term-1182255 | title=Mulder earns another term}}</ref>\n | successor4         = [[Anton Alberts (politician)|Anton Alberts]]\n | office5            = Provincial Leader of the Freedom Front Plus in the North West\n | term_start5        = March 1994\n | term_end5          = March 2017\n | predecessor5       = ''Position established'' \n | successor5         = [[Michal Groenewald]]\n | parliamentarygroup4=  \n | constituency5      =  \n | majority4          =  \n | prior_term4        =  \n | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1955|08|27}}\n | birth_place = \n | death_date = \n | death_place = \n | death_cause = \n | resting_place = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | residence = \n | nationality = [[South Africa]]\n | other_names = \n | known_for = \n | education = [[Potchefstroom University for Christian Higher Education]]\n | alma mater = \n | employer = \n | title =\n | salary = \n | networth = \n | term = \n | party =  [[Freedom Front Plus]]\n | otherparty = [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]]\n | boards = \n | religion =\n | spouse = Hedwig\n | children = \n | parents = \n | relatives = \n}}\n'''Petrus Johannes \"Pieter\" Groenewald''' (born 27 August 1955) is a South African politician. He has been serving as the Leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus]] since his election in November 2016. He started his political career by being elected Mayor of [[Stilfontein]] in 1988. He relinguished the position in 1989 due to his election to the [[House of Assembly (South Africa)|House of Assembly]]. Groenewald co-founded the Freedom Front in 1994, and served as an Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] until his election to the [[North West Provincial Legislature]] in 1999. He returned to the National Assembly in 2001.<ref>[https://www.pa.org.za/person/petrus-johannes-groenewald/#experience Dr Petrus Johannes Groenewald]. ''People's Assembly''. Retrieved on 6 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/south-africa/ff-plus-leader-mulder-steps-down FF Plus leader Mulder steps down], ''eNCA'', 12 November 2016. Retrieved on 7 March 2019.</ref>\n\nGroenewald's son, [[Michal Groenewald|Michal]], also serves as an MP for the FF+.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Besent |first1=Mercedes |title=FF-Plus leader rejects nepotism allegations |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/ff-plus-leader-rejects-nepotism-allegations/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |newspaper=SABC News |date=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPieter Groenewald was born in [[South Africa]]. He achieved a B.luris degree from the [[Potchefstroom University for Christian Higher Education]]. Other degrees that Groenewald has obtained include a Postgraduate Diploma in Communications, a master's degree in Management and Development, and a Doctorate in Politics.<ref>[https://www.vfplus.org.za/latest-news/abridged-cvs-of-the-first-25-candidates-on-the-ff-plus-national-candidate-list Abridged CV's of the first 25 candidates on the FF Plus' National Candidate list], ''VF Plus''. Retrieved on 6 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Pieter Groenewald, FF Plus leader.png|thumb|200px|left|Groenewald delivering a speech at his party's 2019 election manifesto launch]]\nHe was elected Mayor of [[Stilfontein]] in 1988. During the [[1989 South African general election|South African general election of 1989]], Groenewald was elected to the [[House of Assembly of South Africa]] for the Stilfontein constituency.<ref name = \"vf plus\">[https://www.vfplus.org.za/executive-management/dr-pieter-groenewald Dr Pieter Groenewald], ''VF Plus''.</ref>\n\nIn March 1994, Groenewald co-founded the Freedom Front, a minority rights and pro-Afrikaner nationalism political party. He was elected to the newly-established [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] in April of the same year. He served as a Member of Parliament until he was elected to the [[North West Provincial Legislature]] in 1999. He served as a North West MPL from 1999 until he returned to the National Assembly in 2001.<ref name=\"vf plus\" />\n\nGroenewald has held various leadership positions in the [[Freedom Front Plus]], such as Parliamentary Leader and Federal Chairperson from 11 August 2011 until 12 November 2016. He was also the Provincial Leader of the party in the North West from March 1994 to March 2017.<ref name=\"vf plus\" />\n\nOn 12 November 2016, Groenewald was elected Leader of the Freedom Front Plus, succeeding [[Pieter Mulder]], who had announced his intention to stand down.   Advocate [[Anton Alberts (politician)|Anton Alberts]] succeeded Groenewald as Federal Chairperson.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/groenewald-replaces-mulder-as-ff-plus-leader-20161112 Groenewald replaces Mulder as FF Plus leader], ''News24'', 12 November 2016. Retrieved on 6 March 2019.</ref>\n\nGroenewald led the Freedom Front Plus to achieve its best election result in the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general election]]. The party increased its vote share to 2.38% of the national vote, earning it ten seats in the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]]. Its highest representation in the National Assembly since its founding in 1994. Additionally, the party won representation in eight of the nine [[Provincial legislature (South Africa)|provincial legislatures]] and largely improved its showing in the provinces of [[Gauteng]] and the [[North West (South African province)|North West]].<ref>[http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/freedom-front-plus-grows-in-the-northern-provinces/ Freedom Front Plus grows in the Northern Provinces], ''SABC News'', 9 May 2019. Retrieved on 30 June 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-who-are-freedom-front-plus Underdog FF+ grows stronger, polls show], ''eNCA'', 9 May 2019. Retrieved on 30 June 2019.</ref><ref>Mailovich, Claudi. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-09-ff-plus-on-track-to-being-biggest-success-story-of-election-2019/ FF Plus defies expectations], ''BusinessLIVE'', 9 May 2019. Retrieved on 30 June 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/petrus-johannes-groenewald/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/74 Dr Petrus Johannes Groenewald \u2013 Parliament of South Africa]\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Freedom Front Plus}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Groenewald, Pieter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from North West (South African province)]]\n[[Category:North-West University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Freedom Front Plus politicians]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n | name               = Pieter Groenewald\n | native_name        = \n | native_name_lang   = \n | honorific_suffix   = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]] \n | image              = [[File:PJ Groenewald.jpg|220px]]\n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      =\n | smallimage         = \n | alt                = \n | caption            = Groenewald in 2018\n | order              = \n | office             = Leader of the [[Freedom Front Plus]]\n | term_start         =  12 November 2016\n | term_end           = \n | alongside          = \n | monarch            = \n | president          = \n | governor_general   = \n | primeminister      = \n | taoiseach          = \n | chancellor         = \n | governor           = \n | chair              = \n | vicepresident      = \n | viceprimeminister  = \n | deputy             = \n | lieutenant         = \n | vicechair          = \n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or eq